{"title_page": "Leeds Cathedral", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox church\n| name                   = Leeds&nbsp;Cathedral\n| fullname               = Cathedral Church of St Anne\n| image                  = Leeds Cathedral.jpg\n| imagesize              = 300px\n| imagealt               =\n\n| caption                =\n\n| pushpin map            = West Yorkshire\n| pushpin label position = top\n| pushpin map alt        = \n| pushpin mapsize        = \n| map caption            = Shown within West Yorkshire\n| coordinates            = {{coord|53.8007|-1.5468|region:GB|format=dms|display=title}}\n| osgraw                 = <!-- TEXT -->\n| osgridref              = <!-- {{gbmappingsmall|TEXT}} -->\n| location               = [[Leeds]], [[West Yorkshire]]\n| country                = United Kingdom\n\n| denomination           = [[Roman Catholic Church]]\n| tradition              = \n| membership             = \n| website                = [http://www.dioceseofleeds.org.uk/cathedral/ dioceseofleeds.org.uk/cathedral]\n\n| former name            = \n| bull date              = \n| consecrated date       = 1904\n| people                 =\n\n| status                 = \n| functional status      = \n| heritage designation   = Grade II*\n| designated date        = \n| previous cathedrals    = \n| architect              = [[John Henry Eastwood]]\n| architectural type     = \n| style                  = [[Gothic Revival architecture|Neo-gothic]]\n| years built            = 1901-1904\n| groundbreaking         = \n| completed date         = \n| construction cost      = \n| closed date            = \n| demolished date        =\n\n| capacity               = \n| length                 = \n| length nave            = \n| length choir           = \n| width                  = \n| width nave             = \n| width transepts        = \n| height                 = \n| height nave            = \n| height choir           = \n| dome quantity          = \n| dome height outer      = \n| dome height inner      = \n| dome dia outer         = \n| dome dia inner         = \n| tower quantity         = 1\n| tower height           = \n| spire quantity         = \n| spire height           =\n\n| archdiocese            = \n| metropolis             = \n| diocese                = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Leeds|Leeds]]\n| diocese start          = 1878\n| province               = [[Province of Liverpool|Liverpool]]\n| deanery                = Leeds North\n| parish                 = Mother of Unfailing Help\n\n| archbishop             = \n| bishop                 = [[Marcus Stock]] (since 2014)\n| dean                   = Matthew Habron (since 2019)\n| provost                = \n| canon                  = \n| precentor              = \n| archdeacon             =\n\n| reader                 = \n| director               = Benjamin Saunders\n| organist = David Pipe\n| logo                   = \n| logosize               = \n| logolink               = \n| logoalt                = \n}}\n'''Leeds Cathedral''', formally the '''Cathedral Church of St Anne''', commonly known as [[Saint Anne]]'s Cathedral, is the [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] [[Cathedral]] of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Leeds]], and is the seat of the [[Roman Catholic Bishop of Leeds]]. It is in the [[city]] of [[Leeds]], [[West Yorkshire]], [[United Kingdom]]. The city of Leeds does not have a [[Church of England]] [[cathedral]], because though it is in the [[Anglican Diocese of Leeds]], that diocese's cathedrals are in [[Ripon Cathedral|Ripon]], [[Wakefield Cathedral|Wakefield]] and [[Bradford Cathedral|Bradford]].\n\nThe original cathedral was located in St Anne's Church in 1878, but that building was demolished around 1900. The current cathedral building on Cookridge Street was completed in 1904, and was restored in 2006. The [[reredos]] of the old cathedral's high altar was designed by [[Augustus Welby Northmore Pugin|Pugin]] in 1842 and moved to the lady chapel of the new cathedral.<ref name=\"Floorplan\">{{Citation|url=http://www.dioceseofleeds.org.uk/cathedral/cathedral_tour/floorplan.php|title=Floorplan|publisher=Leeds Diocese|accessdate=23 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090131090709/http://www.dioceseofleeds.org.uk/cathedral/cathedral_tour/floorplan.php|archive-date=31 January 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/leeds/content/articles/2007/02/15/faith_st_annes_reredos_feature.shtml|title=Restoring a masterpiece|work=BBC Leeds|accessdate=31 January 2009}}</ref> The cathedral is a Grade II* [[listed building]].<ref name=\"St Anne's RC Cathedral\">{{NHLE |num=1375230 |desc=St Anne's RC Cathedral |accessdate=23 May 2010 |mode=cs2}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Previous Cathedral===\nIn 1786, Lady Lane Chapel was built, the first post-reformation Catholic place of worship in the city. In 1838, it was replaced by St Anne's Church. At the time, there were only two places of Catholic worship in Leeds, St Patrick's Church (which was built in 1831) and St Anne's. The next church to be built in Leeds was [[Mount St Mary's Church, Leeds|Mount St Mary's Church]] in [[Richmond Hill, Leeds|Richmond Hill]].<ref>Fraser, Derek, [https://books.google.com/books?id=4Da8AAAAIAAJ&pg A History of Modern Leeds] (Manchester: Manchester University press, 1980), 256.</ref>\n\nThe earlier St Anne's Roman Catholic Church, built in 1838 on the corner of the [[Headrow]] and Cookridge Street was granted cathedral status in 1878 upon the creation of the Diocese of Leeds.<ref name=\"St Anne's RC Cathedral\"/> The cathedral's life was short-lived as in 1899, [[Leeds City Council|Leeds Corporation]] pushed ahead with plans to widen The Headrow and develop it into a [[Boulevard]] style street. This meant that the cathedral was acquired by the enactment of a [[compulsory purchase order]]. Demolition started shortly after and the [[Leeds Permanent Building Society]] purchased the plot to build its head-office; the site is now [[The Light, Leeds|The Light]] entertainment complex. Church officials considered several sites on which to build the second cathedral but after exhausting other options, the church accepted land offered to it by the corporation, directly adjacent to the previous church.<ref name=\"History\">{{Citation |url=http://www.dioceseofleeds.org.uk/cathedral/history/history.php|title=History |publisher= Leeds Diocese|accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref> Some architectural features of the original building were salvaged and reused in the new building and some can now be seen at the Castle-by-the-Sea Hotel in [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire]], the former residence of the artist [[Atkinson Grimshaw]] who was the father of the first cathedral choir master, [[Arthur E. Grimshaw]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.thecastlebythesea.co.uk/history.html|title=Castle by the Sea|accessdate=21 December 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206155257/http://thecastlebythesea.co.uk/history.html|archivedate=6 February 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Current building===\nThe current cathedral was designed in the [[Arts and Crafts movement|Arts and Crafts]] [[Gothic Revival style]] by [[John Henry Eastwood]] (1843\u20131913), a Leeds-born and London-based architect with previous experience in designing church buildings, much work was also carried out by his assistant, Sydney Kyffin Greenslade (1866\u20131955).<ref name=\"St Anne's RC Cathedral\"/> The layout of the cathedral incorporated no wings, in order to accommodate it on the small site. Building work began in the autumn of 1901 and the cathedral opened in 1904.<ref name=\"History\"/>\n\nAfter renovation in the cathedral (2005\u20132006) [[relic]]s of English Catholic martyrs, [[Peter Snow (priest)|Blessed Peter Snow and Ralph Grimston]], were placed in the altar.{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}}\n\n==Building==\n[[File:Leeds Cathedral (4th May 2010) 001.jpg|thumb|left|Interior (looking towards the altar)]]\nThe cathedral is small in size due to its restricted site.<ref name=\"Floorplan\"/> The cathedral has an aisled nave and chancel under a continuous roof with narrow transepts and chapels. There is a [[chapter house]] and [[Presbytery (architecture)|presbytery]]. It is built of Weldon stone with [[Ketton stone]] details. The west front has a tall gable between large buttresses that end in Gothic turrets.<ref>{{Harvnb|Leach|Pevsner|2009|p=406}}</ref> The western face has a large ornate [[crucifix]] sculpture. The northern face has [[mock-Georgian]] elements to it, including leaded bay windows. The church has a small tower to the north west corner, from which the [[flag of the Vatican City]] is flown{{dubious|date=May 2014}}. The interior has a conventional layout, with rows of pews facing towards the altar, there are two rows of stone pillars set along each side. The ceiling has a barrelled shape, with only a faint apex.\n\n==Liturgy==\n[[File:Vatican City Flag flying atop St Anne's Cathedral.jpg|thumb|right|[[Flag of the Vatican City]] flying atop the Cathedral.]]\nSunday<ref>[https://www.dioceseofleeds.org.uk/cathedral/cathedral-service-times/ Diocese of Leeds: Cathedral Service Times]</ref>\n*18:00 (Saturday) Vigil Mass\n*09:30 Sung Mass\n*11:00 [[Solemn Mass#Non-Tridentine Solemn Mass|Solemn Mass]] (in [[Latin]] on the 1st Sunday of the month)\n*18:00 Mass\n\nMonday-Friday\n*12:00 Angelus & Rosary\n*12:30 Mass\n*15:00-17:00 Exposition of the Blessed Sacrament\n*17:10 Vespers (Sung on Tuesday and Wednesday)\n*17:30 Mass (Sung Monday-Thursday)\n\nSaturday\n*12:00 Mass\n\n==Organs==\nThe 1904 organ by [[Norman and Beard]] was restored in 2010 by [[Klais Orgelbau]]. It has 7 divisions and 55 ranks.<ref name=\"Organ\">{{citation|url=http://www.dioceseofleedsmusic.org.uk/organs/leeds_cathedral.php|title=The Klais Organ|work=Diocese of Leeds Music Department|accessdate=27 November 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315105506/http://www.dioceseofleedsmusic.org.uk/organs/leeds_cathedral.php|archive-date=15 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe Cathedral also houses a chamber organ. This small box organ was manufactured by [[Peter Collins (organ builder)|Peter Collins]] in 1992. It is a portable instrument and is usually located between the choir stalls in the Sanctuary. It is in daily use to accompany [[Gregorian chant]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{Citation|last =Leach|first =Peter| first2 =Nikolaus |last2= Pevsner|author2-link=Nikolaus Pevsner| title =The Buildings of England: Yorkshire West Riding, Leeds, Bradford and the North|publisher =[[Yale University Press]]| year =2009 | location =New Haven and London| isbn =978-0-300-12665-5 }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Leeds Cathedral}}\n*[http://www.dioceseofleeds.org.uk/cathedral/ Leeds Cathedral website]\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Leeds}}\n{{Roman Catholic Cathedrals in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Listed buildings in Leeds}}\n\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches in Leeds]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches completed in 1904]]\n[[Category:Listed buildings in Leeds]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed cathedrals]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed churches in West Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Diocese of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Gothic Revival architecture in Leeds]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox church\n| name                   = Leeds&nbsp;Cathedral\n| fullname               = Cathedral Church of St Anne\n| image                  = Leeds Cathedral.jpg\n| imagesize              = 300px\n| imagealt               =\n\n| caption                =\n\n| pushpin map            = West Yorkshire\n| pushpin label position = top\n| pushpin map alt        = \n| pushpin mapsize        = \n| map caption            = Shown within West Yorkshire\n| coordinates            = {{coord|53.8007|-1.5468|region:GB|format=dms|display=title}}\n| osgraw                 = <!-- TEXT -->\n| osgridref              = <!-- {{gbmappingsmall|TEXT}} -->\n| location               = [[Leeds]], [[West Yorkshire]]\n| country                = United Kingdom\n\n| denomination           = [[Roman Catholic Church]]\n| tradition              = \n| membership             = \n| website                = [http://www.dioceseofleeds.org.uk/cathedral/ dioceseofleeds.org.uk/cathedral]\n\n| former name            = \n| bull date              = \n| consecrated date       = 1904\n| people                 =\n\n| status                 = \n| functional status      = \n| heritage designation   = Grade II*\n| designated date        = \n| previous cathedrals    = \n| architect              = [[John Henry Eastwood]]\n| architectural type     = \n| style                  = [[Gothic Revival architecture|Neo-gothic]]\n| years built            = 1901-1904\n| groundbreaking         = \n| completed date         = \n| construction cost      = \n| closed date            = \n| demolished date        =\n\n| capacity               = \n| length                 = \n| length nave            = \n| length choir           = \n| width                  = \n| width nave             = \n| width transepts        = \n| height                 = \n| height nave            = \n| height choir           = \n| dome quantity          = \n| dome height outer      = \n| dome height inner      = \n| dome dia outer         = \n| dome dia inner         = \n| tower quantity         = 1\n| tower height           = \n| spire quantity         = \n| spire height           =\n\n| archdiocese            = \n| metropolis             = \n| diocese                = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Leeds|Leeds]]\n| diocese start          = 1878\n| province               = [[Province of Liverpool|Liverpool]]\n| deanery                = Leeds North\n| parish                 = Mother of Unfailing Help\n\n| archbishop             = \n| bishop                 = [[Marcus Stock]] (since 2014)\n| dean                   = Matthew Habron (since 2019)\n| provost                = \n| canon                  = \n| precentor              = \n| archdeacon             =\n\n| reader                 = \n| director               = Benjamin Saunders\n| organist = David Pipe\n| logo                   = \n| logosize               = \n| logolink               = \n| logoalt                = \n}}\n'''Leeds Cathedral''', formally the '''Cathedral Church of St Anne''', commonly known as [[Saint Anne]]'s Cathedral, is the [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] [[Cathedral]] of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Leeds]], and is the seat of the [[Roman Catholic Bishop of Leeds]]. It is in the [[city]] of [[Leeds]], [[West Yorkshire]], [[United Kingdom]]. The city of Leeds does not have a [[Church of England]] [[cathedral]], because though it is in the [[Anglican Diocese of Leeds]], that diocese's cathedrals are in [[Ripon Cathedral|Ripon]], [[Wakefield Cathedral|Wakefield]] and [[Bradford Cathedral|Bradford]].\n\nThe original cathedral was located in St Anne's Church in 1878, but that building was demolished around 1900. The current cathedral building on Cookridge Street was completed in 1904, and was restored in 2006. The [[reredos]] of the old cathedral's high altar was designed by [[Augustus Welby Northmore Pugin|Pugin]] in 1842 and moved to the lady chapel of the new cathedral.<ref name=\"Floorplan\">{{Citation|url=http://www.dioceseofleeds.org.uk/cathedral/cathedral_tour/floorplan.php|title=Floorplan|publisher=Leeds Diocese|accessdate=23 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090131090709/http://www.dioceseofleeds.org.uk/cathedral/cathedral_tour/floorplan.php|archive-date=31 January 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/leeds/content/articles/2007/02/15/faith_st_annes_reredos_feature.shtml|title=Restoring a masterpiece|work=BBC Leeds|accessdate=31 January 2009}}</ref> The cathedral is a Grade II* [[listed building]].<ref name=\"St Anne's RC Cathedral\">{{NHLE |num=1375230 |desc=St Anne's RC Cathedral |accessdate=23 May 2010 |mode=cs2}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Previous Cathedral===\nIn 1786, Lady Lane Chapel was built, the first post-reformation Catholic place of worship in the city. In 1838, it was replaced by St Anne's Church. At the time, there were only two places of Catholic worship in Leeds, St Patrick's Church (which was built in 1831) and St Anne's. The next church to be built in Leeds was [[Mount St Mary's Church, Leeds|Mount St Mary's Church]] in [[Richmond Hill, Leeds|Richmond Hill]].<ref>Fraser, Derek, [https://books.google.com/books?id=4Da8AAAAIAAJ&pg A History of Modern Leeds] (Manchester: Manchester University press, 1980), 256.</ref>\n\nThe earlier St Anne's Roman Catholic Church, built in 1838 on the corner of the [[Headrow]] and Cookridge Street was granted cathedral status in 1878 upon the creation of the Diocese of Leeds.<ref name=\"St Anne's RC Cathedral\"/> The cathedral's life was short-lived as in 1899, [[Leeds City Council|Leeds Corporation]] pushed ahead with plans to widen The Headrow and develop it into a [[Boulevard]] style street. This meant that the cathedral was acquired by the enactment of a [[compulsory purchase order]]. Demolition started shortly after and the [[Leeds Permanent Building Society]] purchased the plot to build its head-office, the site is now [[The Light, Leeds|The Light]] entertainment complex. Church officials considered several sites on which to build the second cathedral but after exhausting other options, the church accepted land offered to it by the corporation, directly adjacent to the previous church.<ref name=\"History\">{{Citation |url=http://www.dioceseofleeds.org.uk/cathedral/history/history.php|title=History |publisher= Leeds Diocese|accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref> Some architectural features of the original building were salvaged and reused in the new building and some can now be seen at the Castle-by-the-Sea Hotel in [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire]], the former residence of the artist [[Atkinson Grimshaw]] who was the father of the first cathedral choir master, [[Arthur E. Grimshaw]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.thecastlebythesea.co.uk/history.html|title=Castle by the Sea|accessdate=21 December 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206155257/http://thecastlebythesea.co.uk/history.html|archivedate=6 February 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Current building===\nThe current cathedral was designed in the [[Arts and Crafts movement|Arts and Crafts]] [[Gothic Revival style]] by [[John Henry Eastwood]] (1843\u20131913), a Leeds-born and London-based architect with previous experience in designing church buildings, much work was also carried out by his assistant, Sydney Kyffin Greenslade (1866\u20131955).<ref name=\"St Anne's RC Cathedral\"/> The layout of the cathedral incorporated no wings, in order to accommodate it on the small site. Building work began in the autumn of 1901 and the cathedral opened in 1904.<ref name=\"History\"/>\n\nAfter renovation in the cathedral (2005\u20132006) [[relic]]s of English Catholic martyrs, [[Peter Snow (priest)|Blessed Peter Snow and Ralph Grimston]], were placed in the altar.{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}}\n\n==Building==\n[[File:Leeds Cathedral (4th May 2010) 001.jpg|thumb|left|Interior (looking towards the altar)]]\nThe cathedral is small in size due to its restricted site.<ref name=\"Floorplan\"/> The cathedral has an aisled nave and chancel under a continuous roof with narrow transepts and chapels. There is a [[chapter house]] and [[Presbytery (architecture)|presbytery]]. It is built of Weldon stone with [[Ketton stone]] details. The west front has a tall gable between large buttresses that end in Gothic turrets.<ref>{{Harvnb|Leach|Pevsner|2009|p=406}}</ref> The western face has a large ornate [[crucifix]] sculpture. The northern face has [[mock-Georgian]] elements to it, including leaded bay windows. The church has a small tower to the north west corner, from which the [[flag of the Vatican City]] is flown{{dubious|date=May 2014}}. The interior has a conventional layout, with rows of pews facing towards the altar, there are two rows of stone pillars set along each side. The ceiling has a barrelled shape, with only a faint apex.\n\n==Liturgy==\n[[File:Vatican City Flag flying atop St Anne's Cathedral.jpg|thumb|right|[[Flag of the Vatican City]] flying atop the Cathedral.]]\nSunday<ref>[https://www.dioceseofleeds.org.uk/cathedral/cathedral-service-times/ Diocese of Leeds: Cathedral Service Times]</ref>\n*18:00 (Saturday) Vigil Mass\n*09:30 Sung Mass\n*11:00 [[Solemn Mass#Non-Tridentine Solemn Mass|Solemn Mass]] (in [[Latin]] on the 1st Sunday of the month)\n*18:00 Mass\n\nMonday-Friday\n*12:00 Angelus & Rosary\n*12:30 Mass\n*15:00-17:00 Exposition of the Blessed Sacrament\n*17:10 Vespers (Sung on Tuesday and Wednesday)\n*17:30 Mass (Sung Monday-Thursday)\n\nSaturday\n*12:00 Mass\n\n==Organs==\nThe 1904 organ by [[Norman and Beard]] was restored in 2010 by [[Klais Orgelbau]]. It has 7 divisions and 55 ranks.<ref name=\"Organ\">{{citation|url=http://www.dioceseofleedsmusic.org.uk/organs/leeds_cathedral.php|title=The Klais Organ|work=Diocese of Leeds Music Department|accessdate=27 November 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315105506/http://www.dioceseofleedsmusic.org.uk/organs/leeds_cathedral.php|archive-date=15 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe Cathedral also houses a chamber organ. This small box organ was manufactured by [[Peter Collins (organ builder)|Peter Collins]] in 1992. It is a portable instrument and is usually located between the choir stalls in the Sanctuary. It is in daily use to accompany [[Gregorian chant]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{Citation|last =Leach|first =Peter| first2 =Nikolaus |last2= Pevsner|author2-link=Nikolaus Pevsner| title =The Buildings of England: Yorkshire West Riding, Leeds, Bradford and the North|publisher =[[Yale University Press]]| year =2009 | location =New Haven and London| isbn =978-0-300-12665-5 }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Leeds Cathedral}}\n*[http://www.dioceseofleeds.org.uk/cathedral/ Leeds Cathedral website]\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Leeds}}\n{{Roman Catholic Cathedrals in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Listed buildings in Leeds}}\n\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches in Leeds]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches completed in 1904]]\n[[Category:Listed buildings in Leeds]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed cathedrals]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed churches in West Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Diocese of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Gothic Revival architecture in Leeds]]\n", "name_user": "Chrism", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePrevious Cathedral", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leeds_Cathedral"}
{"title_page": "Abbey Clancy", "text_new": "{{short description|English lingerie and catwalk model and television personality}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox model\n| name          = Abbey Clancy\n| image         = Abby Clancy (crop).jpg\n| caption       = Clancy in 2012\n| birth_name    = Abigail Marie Clancy\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1986|01|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Liverpool|Liverpool, Merseyside]], England\n| height        = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}\n| haircolour     = Blonde\n| eyecolour      = Green\n| agency        =\n| spouse        = {{marriage|[[Peter Crouch]]|30 June 2011}}\n| children      = 4\n| relations     = [[Sean Clancy]] (brother)\n}}\n\n'''Abigail Marie Clancy,''' (born 10 January 1986) known as '''Abbey Clancy''', is an English [[lingerie]] and [[catwalk model]] and [[television personality]]. She is married to former professional footballer [[Peter Crouch]], was the runner-up of ''[[Britain's Next Top Model (cycle 2)]]'' in 2006 and won [[Strictly Come Dancing (series 11)|series 11]] of ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'' in 2013.<ref name=Strictly>{{cite web|last1=Barnes|first1=Anthony|title=Strictly Come Dancing 2013: Abbey Clancy crowned champion as more than 12m watch the final|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/strictly-come-dancing-2013-abbey-clancy-crowned-champion-as-more-than-12m-watch-9020780.html|work=The Independent|accessdate=6 October 2014|date=22 December 2013}}</ref> Since 2015 she has been presenting ''[[Britain's Next Top Model]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nClancy was born in [[Liverpool]], the youngest of four children of Karen (n\u00e9e Sullivan) and Geoffrey Thomas Clancy. She grew up in Woolton, an upper class suburb of Liverpool and she attended St Mary's Primary School and St Julies Secondary School.  Clancy formed girl band ''Genie Queen'', who were managed by [[Andy McCluskey]] from [[Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark]] (OMD).<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/liverpool/music/2003/09/geniequeen/index.shtml | title = Three Wishes for Genie Queen | work = [[BBC]] | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20031009054735/http://www.bbc.co.uk/liverpool/music/2003/09/geniequeen/index.shtml | archivedate = 9 October 2003 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Modelling===\n[[File:Abbey Clancy at Lingerie london.jpg|thumb|Clancy on the Catwalk in 2012]]\nIn summer 2006, the [[Britain's Next Top Model, Cycle 2|second cycle]] of [[Living TV]]'s ''[[Britain's Next Top Model]]'' included Clancy as one of the thirteen finalists in the competition, competing over 10 weeks for a modelling contract. Clancy made it to the final runway show with fellow contestant Lianna Fowler, eventually becoming the runner up.\n\nAfter appearing on ''Britain's Next Top Model'', Clancy modelled for several magazines and newspapers. In May 2007, Clancy appeared on the cover of ''[[Arena]]'' magazine,<ref>{{cite web|title=Abigail Clancy |url= http://www.fashionmodeldirectory.com/models/abigail_clancy/showphoto/85258/|work=[[Fashion Model Directory]]|accessdate=2 January 2011}}</ref> and modelled the [[Triumph Bonneville]] [[Motorbike]] in the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' newspaper.<ref>[http://www.fhm.com/girls/abbey-clancy-the-interview-20081007 Abbey Clancy: Pefect<!-- sic -->... apart from the boyfriend]{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405012423/http://www.fhm.com/girls/abbey-clancy-the-interview-20081007 |date=5 April 2012 }}, FHM.com (7 October 2008). Retrieved on 5 May 2012.</ref>\nClancy was chosen to appear in ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' magazine in the 2010 [[Sports Illustrated Swimsuit Issue|swimsuit edition]]. Clancy was featured for her sporting connection to [[Peter Crouch]] and was photographed for the magazine wearing only body paint to make it appear as if she was wearing an England shirt, shot by [[Yu Tsai]].<ref>{{youtube|KxGYReHyRIw|Body Painting \u2013 Abbey Clancy (Sports Illustrated Feb 2010)}}</ref><ref>[http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010_swimsuit/painting/abbey-clancy/ Abbey Clancy] [[bodypaint]] shoot for [[Sports Illustrated]]</ref>\n\nClancy appeared in a 2010 campaign for ''[[Umbro]]'' sportswear, modelling an England shirt, along with other [[WAGs|footballer's wives and girlfriends]] from countries that have won the World Cup. Clancy walked in the [[Giles Deacon]] Ready-To-Wear line Giles Spring 2011 collection.<ref>{{cite news |title= Pregnant Abby Clancy Walks in Giles\u2019s Spring Show, Veruschka Closes |url= http://nymag.com/daily/fashion/2010/09/pregnant_abby_clancy_walks_in.html |work= [[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date= 21 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2011 Clancy appeared on the Elite Model Management: New York division website. In July 2013, she appeared as part of London designer Hasan Hejazi's campaign, in a fashion editorial by Absynth Photographic and a fashion film by Gabriel Gettman. Clancy also modelled for the August 2011 cover of UK ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' shot by photographer S\u00f8lve Sundsb\u00f8.\n\nIn December 2013 Clancy was featured in ''[[LOVE (magazine)|LOVE]]'' magazine's Advent Calendar alongside [[Suki Waterhouse]] and [[Cara Delevingne]].\n\nIn July 2014, Clancy appeared on the cover of British ''[[Marie Claire]]'' and in March 2015, British ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]''.\n\nIn October 2019, Abbey Clancy and her daughter Sophia Crouch collaborated with Lipsy, a London-based fashion brand, for the Launch of  their AW\u201919 collection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://evoke.ie/2019/10/16/style/fashion-fix/abbey-clancys-daughter-sophia|title=Abbey Clancy's eight-year-old daughter makes modelling debut for Lipsy|last=Neill|first=Bronwyn O.|date=2019-10-16|website=EVOKE.ie|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref> In January 2020, the AW\u201919 collection was launched in UAE.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uaenews247.com/2019/12/25/lipsy-london-launches-the-abbey-and-sophias-aw19-collection-in-the-uae/|title=LIPSY LONDON LAUNCHES THE ABBEY AND SOPHIA\u2019S AW\u201919 COLLECTION IN THE UAE|last=uaenews247|date=2019-12-25|website=UAE News 24/7|language=en|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref>\n\n===Television===\n{{BLP sources section|date =October 2014}}\nClancy has appeared as a [[wiktionary:talking head|talking head]] in the documentaries ''Slave to Fashion'' and ''The Ultimate Bikini Guide'' for [[Channel 4]], as a guest on programmes such as ''[[Richard & Judy]]'', ''[[The Chris Moyles Show]]'', ''[[Friday Night with Jonathan Ross]]'', ''[[GMTV]]'', ''[[This Morning (TV series)|This Morning]]'' and in her own [[Reality television|reality TV]] series ''[[Janice & Abbey|Abbey and Janice: Beauty and the Best]]'' which followed her attempts to break the Los Angeles modelling scene with [[Janice Dickinson]] as her mentor. The show aired from 14 May to 18 June 2007 on [[Living TV]].\n\nClancy featured in the third series of ''[[Hell's Kitchen (UK TV series)|Hell's Kitchen]]''.<ref>{{cite web | title = Abigail's Hell's Kitchen profile | url = http://www.itv.com/Entertainment/reality/hellskitchen/thecelebrities/AbigailClancy/default.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929122827/http://www.itv.com/Entertainment/reality/hellskitchen/thecelebrities/AbigailClancy/default.html | archivedate = 29 September 2007 | accessdate = 11 November 2009 }}</ref> She was the third contestant to be voted off the show by the public, and the fifth to leave overall.\n\nOn 10 May 2009, Clancy featured on ''[[Chris Moyles' Quiz Night]]'' alongside [[Patsy Kensit]]. She won her episode and was the overall winner of the first series.\n\nClancy also co-hosted the [[ITV2]] series, ''The Fashion Show'' with model Michelle de Swarte and [[George Lamb]].<ref>{{cite news | date = 12 May 2008 | first = Dave | last = West | title = ITV2 sets fashion show with Clancy, Lamb | url = http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/a95753/itv2-sets-fashion-show-with-clancy-lamb.html | publisher = [[Digital Spy]] | accessdate = 13 May 2008 }}</ref> Her cousin [[Chloe Cummings]], made the top 13 contestants in the [[Britain's Next Top Model, Cycle 5|fifth cycle]] of ''Britain's Next Top Model'', of which Clancy herself was a guest in episode 8, being the first ex-contestant from the Top Model franchise to appear on the judging panel.\n\nOn 22 December 2009, Clancy appeared as a \"contestant\" on a spoof version of ''[[Blind Date (UK TV series)|Blind Date]]'' as part of an episode of ''[[Alan Carr: Chatty Man]]'' in which [[Cilla Black]] was a guest.\n\nIn April 2010, Clancy was featured in ITV2's ''The Parent Trip'' along with her mother Karen.  She also appeared as a panellist on ''A League of Their Own''.\n\nClancy was a regular guest on ''[[James Corden's World Cup Live]]''.\n\nShe also co-hosted the reality TV show ''Great British Hairdresser'' in 2011.\n\nIn 2013, Clancy won the eleventh series of ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]''. Her professional partner was newcomer and ''Burn the Floor'' dancer, [[Alja\u017e Skorjanec]]. On 16 November 2013, they received their first \"10s\" of the competition, during ''[[Blackpool]] Week''. On 30 November 2013, they became the first couple that year to score a perfect \"40\", during ''Musicals Week''.<ref name=Strictly/>\n\nIn 2015, Clancy was announced as the new host for a revived series of ''[[Britain's Next Top Model]]'', nine years after she began her own career on the show.<ref>{{cite news| date = 26 August 2014 | first = Kate | last = Thomas | title = Abbey Clancy to make comeback to Britain's Next Top Model as a judge | url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-3211344/Abbey-Clancy-make-comeback-Britain-s-Model-judge.html | work = [[Daily Mail]] | accessdate = 23 December 2015 }}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=November 2019}}\n\n===Book===\nIn March 2016, Clancy's first book, ''Remember My Name'', was published.\n\n==Other media==\nIn 2019, Clancy cameoed as an angel in the promotional video for the song \"In Another Life\" by British rock band [[The Darkness (band)|The Darkness]].<ref> https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G7H4VjjAPmE </ref>\n\n==Media recognition==\nClancy was ranked 37th in ''FHM'' magazine's [[annual publication|annual]] ''[[FHM's 100 Sexiest Women (UK)|100 sexiest women in the world]]'' poll of 2007 but dropped down to number 55 the following year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fhm.com/girls/100-sexiest/100-sexiest-2008---the-results-20081207 |title=FHM 100 Top sexiest women |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091001042824/http://www.fhm.com/girls/100-sexiest/100-sexiest-2008---the-results-20081207 |archivedate=1 October 2009 }}</ref> In 2009, Clancy had moved up to 12th place,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fhm.com/girls/covergirls/Abbey-Clancy |title=Abbey Clancy at FHM.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090831052942/http://www.fhm.com/girls/covergirls/Abbey-Clancy |archivedate=31 August 2009 }}</ref> and in 2010 she went up to 10th place in the annual poll.<ref>{{cite news | date = 29 April 2010 | author = Tina Miles | title = Liverpool model Abbey Clancy named among top 10 of the world\u2019s sexiest women | url = http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/liverpool-news/local-news/2010/04/29/liverpool-model-abbey-clancy-named-among-top-10-of-the-world-s-sexiest-women-100252-26339211/ | newspaper = [[Liverpool Echo]] | accessdate = 6 May 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | date = 29 April 2010 | title = Full list of FHM's top 100 world's sexiest women 2010. Cheryl Cole, Megan Fox and Marissa Miller have topped FHM's sexiest women poll for 2010, but Sienna Miller, Charlotte Church and Billie Piper have struggled to perform. | url = http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/823886-full-list-of-fhms-top-100-worlds-sexiest-women | newspaper = [[Metro (Associated Metro Limited)|Metro]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | date = 29 April 2010 | title = Cheryl Cole 'sexiest woman' for second year | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8651399.stm | work = [[BBC News]] | publisher = BBC Corp }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2012 ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun Newspaper]]'' announced Clancy as their exclusive Beauty Columnist writer. Clancy was the subject of widespread criticism in her home town of [[Liverpool]], as the paper was boycotted in the city for printing false allegations against supporters of [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool football club]] in the aftermath of the [[Hillsborough disaster]] in 1989. Clancy later apologised for the column.<ref>[http://www.clickliverpool.com/news/local-news/1217240-former-liverpool-wag-abbey-clancy-issues-apology-over-sun-beauty-column.html Former Liverpool WAG Abbey Clancy issues apology over Sun beauty column] {{webarchive |url=https://archive.is/20130119070314/http://www.clickliverpool.com/news/local-news/1217240-former-liverpool-wag-abbey-clancy-issues-apology-over-sun-beauty-column.html |date=19 January 2013 }}. clickliverpool.com (16 September 2012). Retrieved on 7 November 2012.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nClancy's brother [[Sean Clancy|Sean]] is a [[association football|footballer]] who played for [[A.F.C. Telford United]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Abbey Clancy: The interview |publisher=FHM.com |date=10 December 2006 |url=http://www.fhm.com/girls/abbey-clancy-the-interview-20061210 |quote=I also support Southport, though, because my brother Sean plays left wing for them. He's fantastic. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081214181207/http://www.fhm.com/girls/abbey-clancy-the-interview-20061210 |archivedate=14 December 2008 }}</ref> He was also a castmember of the short-lived [[E4 (TV channel)|E4]] reality series ''[[Desperate Scousewives]]''.\n\nShe started dating footballer [[Peter Crouch]] in 2006. The couple were engaged from July 2009 and their daughter Sophia Ruby was born on 14 March 2011.\n\nOn 30 June 2011, Clancy and Crouch married. Their second daughter Liberty Rose was born on 1 June 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/abbey-clancy-gives-birth-coleen-5810767|title=Abbey Clancy gives birth: Coleen Rooney, Michelle Keegan and more pass on congratulations as couple welcome daughter|author=Rebecca Pocklington|date=2 June 2015|work=Daily Mirror|accessdate=9 December 2015}}</ref> Their son, Johnny, was born on 3 January 2018. It was announced by Peter on 3 January 2019 that the couple were expecting their fourth child. On 3 June 2019, Abbey gave birth to their second son.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Abbey Clancy}}\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071011163442/http://www.fhm.com/abbeyclancy Abbey Clancy] on [[FHM|FHM.com]]\n* {{Fashionmodel|name=Abigail Clancy}}\n* {{IMDb name|2325706|Abigail Clancy}}\n<!-- Please read [[WP:EL]] before adding more external links -->\n\n{{Strictly Come Dancing}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clancy, Abigail}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Models from Merseyside]]\n[[Category:Footballers' wives and girlfriends]]\n[[Category:Strictly Come Dancing winners]]\n[[Category:Top Model finalists]]\n[[Category:Television presenters from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:British female models]]\n[[Category:Britain & Ireland's Next Top Model contestants]]\n[[Category:Women television presenters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English lingerie and catwalk model and television personality}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox model\n| name          = Abbey Clancy\n| image         = Abby Clancy (crop).jpg\n| caption       = Clancy in 2012\n| birth_name    = Abigail Marie Clancy\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1986|01|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Liverpool|Liverpool, Merseyside]], England\n| height        = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}\n| haircolour     = Blonde\n| eyecolour      = Green\n| agency        =\n| spouse        = {{marriage|[[Peter Crouch]]|30 June 2011}}\n| children      = 4\n| relations     = [[Sean Clancy]] (brother)\n}}\n\n'''Abigail Marie Clancy,''' (born 10 January 1986) known as '''Abbey Clancy''', is an English [[lingerie]] and [[catwalk model]] and [[television personality]]. She is married to former professional footballer [[Peter Crouch]], was the runner-up of ''[[Britain's Next Top Model (cycle 2)]]'' in 2006 and won [[Strictly Come Dancing (series 11)|series 11]] of ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'' in 2013.<ref name=Strictly>{{cite web|last1=Barnes|first1=Anthony|title=Strictly Come Dancing 2013: Abbey Clancy crowned champion as more than 12m watch the final|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/strictly-come-dancing-2013-abbey-clancy-crowned-champion-as-more-than-12m-watch-9020780.html|work=The Independent|accessdate=6 October 2014|date=22 December 2013}}</ref> Since 2015 she has been presenting ''[[Britain's Next Top Model]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nClancy was born in [[Liverpool]], the youngest of four children of Karen (n\u00e9e Sullivan) and Geoffrey Thomas Clancy. She grew up in Woolton, an upper class suburb of Liverpool and she attended St Mary's Primary School and St Julies Secondary School.  Clancy formed girl band ''Genie Queen'', who were managed by [[Andy McCluskey]] from [[Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark]] (OMD).<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/liverpool/music/2003/09/geniequeen/index.shtml | title = Three Wishes for Genie Queen | work = [[BBC]] | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20031009054735/http://www.bbc.co.uk/liverpool/music/2003/09/geniequeen/index.shtml | archivedate = 9 October 2003 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Modelling===\n[[File:Abbey Clancy at Lingerie london.jpg|thumb|Clancy on the Catwalk in 2012]]\nIn summer 2006, the [[Britain's Next Top Model, Cycle 2|second cycle]] of [[Living TV]]'s ''[[Britain's Next Top Model]]'' included Clancy as one of the thirteen finalists in the competition, competing over 10 weeks for a modelling contract. Clancy made it to the final runway show with fellow contestant Lianna Fowler, eventually becoming the runner up.\n\nAfter appearing on ''Britain's Next Top Model'', Clancy modelled for several magazines and newspapers. In May 2007, Clancy appeared on the cover of ''[[Arena]]'' magazine,<ref>{{cite web|title=Abigail Clancy |url= http://www.fashionmodeldirectory.com/models/abigail_clancy/showphoto/85258/|work=[[Fashion Model Directory]]|accessdate=2 January 2011}}</ref> and modelled the [[Triumph Bonneville]] [[Motorbike]] in the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' newspaper.<ref>[http://www.fhm.com/girls/abbey-clancy-the-interview-20081007 Abbey Clancy: Pefect<!-- sic -->... apart from the boyfriend]{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405012423/http://www.fhm.com/girls/abbey-clancy-the-interview-20081007 |date=5 April 2012 }}, FHM.com (7 October 2008). Retrieved on 5 May 2012.</ref>\nClancy was chosen to appear in ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' magazine in the 2010 [[Sports Illustrated Swimsuit Issue|swimsuit edition]]. Clancy was featured for her sporting connection to [[Peter Crouch]] and was photographed for the magazine wearing only body paint to make it appear as if she was wearing an England shirt, shot by [[Yu Tsai]].<ref>{{youtube|KxGYReHyRIw|Body Painting \u2013 Abbey Clancy (Sports Illustrated Feb 2010)}}</ref><ref>[http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010_swimsuit/painting/abbey-clancy/ Abbey Clancy] [[bodypaint]] shoot for [[Sports Illustrated]]</ref>\n\nClancy appeared in a 2010 campaign for ''[[Umbro]]'' sportswear, modelling an England shirt, along with other [[WAGs|footballer's wives and girlfriends]] from countries that have won the World Cup. Clancy walked in the [[Giles Deacon]] Ready-To-Wear line Giles Spring 2011 collection.<ref>{{cite news |title= Pregnant Abby Clancy Walks in Giles\u2019s Spring Show, Veruschka Closes |url= http://nymag.com/daily/fashion/2010/09/pregnant_abby_clancy_walks_in.html |work= [[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date= 21 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2011 Clancy appeared on the Elite Model Management: New York division website. In July 2013, she appeared as part of London designer Hasan Hejazi's campaign, in a fashion editorial by Absynth Photographic and a fashion film by Gabriel Gettman. Clancy also modelled for the August 2011 cover of UK ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' shot by photographer S\u00f8lve Sundsb\u00f8.\n\nIn December 2013 Clancy was featured in ''[[LOVE (magazine)|LOVE]]'' magazine's Advent Calendar alongside [[Suki Waterhouse]] and [[Cara Delevingne]].\n\nIn July 2014, Clancy appeared on the cover of British ''[[Marie Claire]]'' and in March 2015, British ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]''.\n\nIn October 2019, Abbey Clancy and her daughter Sophia Crouch collaborated with Lipsy, a London-based fashion brand, for the Launch of  their AW\u201919 collection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://evoke.ie/2019/10/16/style/fashion-fix/abbey-clancys-daughter-sophia|title=Abbey Clancy's eight-year-old daughter makes modelling debut for Lipsy|last=Neill|first=Bronwyn O.|date=2019-10-16|website=EVOKE.ie|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref> In January 2020, the AW\u201919 collection was launched in UAE.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uaenews247.com/2019/12/25/lipsy-london-launches-the-abbey-and-sophias-aw19-collection-in-the-uae/|title=LIPSY LONDON LAUNCHES THE ABBEY AND SOPHIA\u2019S AW\u201919 COLLECTION IN THE UAE|last=uaenews247|date=2019-12-25|website=UAE News 24/7|language=en|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref>\n\n===Television===\n{{BLP sources section|date =October 2014}}\nClancy has appeared as a [[wiktionary:talking head|talking head]] in the documentaries ''Slave to Fashion'' and ''The Ultimate Bikini Guide'' for [[Channel 4]], as a guest on programmes such as ''[[Richard & Judy]]'', ''[[The Chris Moyles Show]]'', ''[[Friday Night with Jonathan Ross]]'', ''[[GMTV]]'', ''[[This Morning (TV series)|This Morning]]'' and in her own [[Reality television|reality TV]] series ''[[Janice & Abbey|Abbey and Janice: Beauty and the Best]]'' which followed her attempts to break the Los Angeles modelling scene with [[Janice Dickinson]] as her mentor. The show aired from 14 May to 18 June 2007 on [[Living TV]].\n\nClancy featured in the third series of ''[[Hell's Kitchen (UK TV series)|Hell's Kitchen]]''.<ref>{{cite web | title = Abigail's Hell's Kitchen profile | url = http://www.itv.com/Entertainment/reality/hellskitchen/thecelebrities/AbigailClancy/default.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929122827/http://www.itv.com/Entertainment/reality/hellskitchen/thecelebrities/AbigailClancy/default.html | archivedate = 29 September 2007 | accessdate = 11 November 2009 }}</ref> She was the third contestant to be voted off the show by the public, and the fifth to leave overall.\n\nOn 10 May 2009, Clancy featured on ''[[Chris Moyles' Quiz Night]]'' alongside [[Patsy Kensit]]. She won her episode and was the overall winner of the first series.\n\nClancy also co-hosted the [[ITV2]] series, ''The Fashion Show'' with model Michelle de Swarte and [[George Lamb]].<ref>{{cite news | date = 12 May 2008 | first = Dave | last = West | title = ITV2 sets fashion show with Clancy, Lamb | url = http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/a95753/itv2-sets-fashion-show-with-clancy-lamb.html | publisher = [[Digital Spy]] | accessdate = 13 May 2008 }}</ref> Her cousin [[Chloe Cummings]], made the top 13 contestants in the [[Britain's Next Top Model, Cycle 5|fifth cycle]] of ''Britain's Next Top Model'', of which Clancy herself was a guest in episode 8, being the first ex-contestant from the Top Model franchise to appear on the judging panel.\n\nOn 22 December 2009, Clancy appeared as a \"contestant\" on a spoof version of ''[[Blind Date (UK TV series)|Blind Date]]'' as part of an episode of ''[[Alan Carr: Chatty Man]]'' in which [[Cilla Black]] was a guest.\n\nIn April 2010, Clancy was featured in ITV2's ''The Parent Trip'' along with her mother Karen.  She also appeared as a panellist on ''A League of Their Own''.\n\nClancy was a regular guest on ''[[James Corden's World Cup Live]]''.\n\nShe also co-hosted the reality TV show ''Great British Hairdresser'' in 2011.\n\nIn 2013, Clancy won the eleventh series of ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]''. Her professional partner was newcomer and ''Burn the Floor'' dancer, [[Alja\u017e Skorjanec]]. On 16 November 2013, they received their first \"10s\" of the competition, during ''[[Blackpool]] Week''. On 30 November 2013, they became the first couple that year to score a perfect \"40\", during ''Musicals Week''.<ref name=Strictly/>\n\nIn 2015, Clancy was announced as the new host for a revived series of ''[[Britain's Next Top Model]]'', 9 years after she began her own career on the show.<ref>{{cite news| date = 26 August 2014 | first = Kate | last = Thomas | title = Abbey Clancy to make comeback to Britain's Next Top Model as a judge | url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-3211344/Abbey-Clancy-make-comeback-Britain-s-Model-judge.html | work = [[Daily Mail]] | accessdate = 23 December 2015 }}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=November 2019}}\n\n===Book===\nIn March 2016, Clancy's first book, ''Remember My Name'', was published.\n\n==Other media==\nIn 2019, Clancy cameoed as an angel in the promotional video for the song \"In Another Life\" by British rock band [[The Darkness (band)|The Darkness]].<ref> https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G7H4VjjAPmE </ref>\n\n==Media recognition==\nClancy was ranked 37th in ''FHM'' magazine's [[annual publication|annual]] ''[[FHM's 100 Sexiest Women (UK)|100 sexiest women in the world]]'' poll of 2007 but dropped down to number 55 the following year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fhm.com/girls/100-sexiest/100-sexiest-2008---the-results-20081207 |title=FHM 100 Top sexiest women |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091001042824/http://www.fhm.com/girls/100-sexiest/100-sexiest-2008---the-results-20081207 |archivedate=1 October 2009 }}</ref> In 2009, Clancy had moved up to 12th place,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fhm.com/girls/covergirls/Abbey-Clancy |title=Abbey Clancy at FHM.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090831052942/http://www.fhm.com/girls/covergirls/Abbey-Clancy |archivedate=31 August 2009 }}</ref> and in 2010 she went up to 10th place in the annual poll.<ref>{{cite news | date = 29 April 2010 | author = Tina Miles | title = Liverpool model Abbey Clancy named among top 10 of the world\u2019s sexiest women | url = http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/liverpool-news/local-news/2010/04/29/liverpool-model-abbey-clancy-named-among-top-10-of-the-world-s-sexiest-women-100252-26339211/ | newspaper = [[Liverpool Echo]] | accessdate = 6 May 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | date = 29 April 2010 | title = Full list of FHM's top 100 world's sexiest women 2010. Cheryl Cole, Megan Fox and Marissa Miller have topped FHM's sexiest women poll for 2010, but Sienna Miller, Charlotte Church and Billie Piper have struggled to perform. | url = http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/823886-full-list-of-fhms-top-100-worlds-sexiest-women | newspaper = [[Metro (Associated Metro Limited)|Metro]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | date = 29 April 2010 | title = Cheryl Cole 'sexiest woman' for second year | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8651399.stm | work = [[BBC News]] | publisher = BBC Corp }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2012 ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun Newspaper]]'' announced Clancy as their exclusive Beauty Columnist writer. Clancy was the subject of widespread criticism in her home town of [[Liverpool]], as the paper was boycotted in the city for printing false allegations against supporters of [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool football club]] in the aftermath of the [[Hillsborough disaster]] in 1989. Clancy later apologised for the column.<ref>[http://www.clickliverpool.com/news/local-news/1217240-former-liverpool-wag-abbey-clancy-issues-apology-over-sun-beauty-column.html Former Liverpool WAG Abbey Clancy issues apology over Sun beauty column] {{webarchive |url=https://archive.is/20130119070314/http://www.clickliverpool.com/news/local-news/1217240-former-liverpool-wag-abbey-clancy-issues-apology-over-sun-beauty-column.html |date=19 January 2013 }}. clickliverpool.com (16 September 2012). Retrieved on 7 November 2012.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nClancy's brother [[Sean Clancy|Sean]] is a [[association football|footballer]] who played for [[A.F.C. Telford United]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Abbey Clancy: The interview |publisher=FHM.com |date=10 December 2006 |url=http://www.fhm.com/girls/abbey-clancy-the-interview-20061210 |quote=I also support Southport, though, because my brother Sean plays left wing for them. He's fantastic. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081214181207/http://www.fhm.com/girls/abbey-clancy-the-interview-20061210 |archivedate=14 December 2008 }}</ref> He was also a castmember of the short-lived [[E4 (TV channel)|E4]] reality series ''[[Desperate Scousewives]]''.\n\nShe started dating footballer [[Peter Crouch]] in 2006. The couple were engaged from July 2009 and their daughter Sophia Ruby was born on 14 March 2011.\n\nOn 30 June 2011, Clancy and Crouch married. Their second daughter Liberty Rose was born on 1 June 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/abbey-clancy-gives-birth-coleen-5810767|title=Abbey Clancy gives birth: Coleen Rooney, Michelle Keegan and more pass on congratulations as couple welcome daughter|author=Rebecca Pocklington|date=2 June 2015|work=Daily Mirror|accessdate=9 December 2015}}</ref> Their son, Johnny, was born on 3 January 2018. It was announced by Peter on 3 January 2019 that the couple were expecting their fourth child. On 3 June 2019, Abbey gave birth to their second son.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Abbey Clancy}}\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071011163442/http://www.fhm.com/abbeyclancy Abbey Clancy] on [[FHM|FHM.com]]\n* {{Fashionmodel|name=Abigail Clancy}}\n* {{IMDb name|2325706|Abigail Clancy}}\n<!-- Please read [[WP:EL]] before adding more external links -->\n\n{{Strictly Come Dancing}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clancy, Abigail}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Models from Merseyside]]\n[[Category:Footballers' wives and girlfriends]]\n[[Category:Strictly Come Dancing winners]]\n[[Category:Top Model finalists]]\n[[Category:Television presenters from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:British female models]]\n[[Category:Britain & Ireland's Next Top Model contestants]]\n[[Category:Women television presenters]]\n", "name_user": "Notreallydavid", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abbey_Clancy"}
{"title_page": "Toyota Celica LB Turbo", "text_new": "{{Infobox racing car\n| Car_name = Toyota Celica LB Turbo\n| Image = \n| Category = [[Group 5 (racing)|Group 5]] [[sportscar racing|sportscar racer]]\n| Constructor = [[Toyota]]\n| Designer = \n| Team = [[Schnitzer Motorsport]]<br>[[TOM'S]]<br>[[GReddy|Trust Japan]]\n| Drivers = [[Harald Ertl]]<br>[[Rolf Stommelen]]<br>[[Nobuhide Tachi]]<br>Kaoru Hoshino<br>Tatsuhiko Kaneumi\n| Technical ref = <!-- <ref name=tech>Insert formatted reference</ref> -->\n| Chassis = \n| Rear suspension = \n| Front suspension = \n| Length = <!-- Use: {{convert|XXX|in|cm|1|abbr=on}} -->\n| Width = <!-- Use: {{convert|XXX|in|cm|1|abbr=on}} -->\n| Height = <!-- Use: {{convert|XXX|in|cm|1|abbr=on}} -->\n| Wheelbase = {{convert|95.3|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| Track = <!-- Use: {{convert|XXX|in|cm|1|abbr=on}} -->\n| Engine name = [[Toyota R engine#18R-G|Toyota 18R-G]]\n| Capacity = {{convert|2090|cc|cuin|1|abbr=on}}\n| Configuration = [[Inline-four engine|I4]]\n| Turbo/NA = [[Turbocharger]]\n| Engine position = [[Front-engine design|Front-engine]]d, [[longitudinal engine|longitudinally mounted]]\n| Gearbox name = \n| Gears = 5-speed\n| Type = [[manual transmission]]\n| Differential = \n| Weight = {{convert|860|kg|lb|1|abbr=on}}\n| Fuel = [[Royal Dutch Shell|Shell]]\n| Tyres = [[Dunlop Rubber|Dunlop]]\n| Debut = 1977 DRM Hockenheim\n| Races = 21\n| Wins = 2\n| Cons_champ = \n| Drivers_champ = \n| Teams_champ = \n| Poles = \n| Fastest_laps = \n}}\nThe '''Toyota Celica LB Turbo''' was a [[Group 5 (racing)|Group 5 Special Production]] [[racecar]] version of the 3-door liftback [[Toyota Celica#First generation / A20/35 Series (1970\u20131977)|first generation Toyota Celica GT]] built by [[Schnitzer Motorsport|Schnitzer]] via [[Toyota]] Deutschland to compete in Division 1 of the [[Deutsche Rennsport Meisterschaft|DRM]].\n\nIt competed in the [[Germany|German]] series in 1977 and 1978. Plagued by reliability problems, it finished twice and won a non-championship race. At the end of its [[Europe]]an career, it went on to compete in [[Japan]] with minor success.\n\nThroughout its competitive seasons, it was the only non-German car to compete in the top division of the German series.<ref name=\"wspr-drm1977\" /><ref name=\"wspr-drm1978\" />\n\n==Development==\nThe A20 Celica was built to compete against the [[Porsche 935]]s that had dominated international [[motorsport]] and also the Division 1 of the German DRM series for Group 5 cars. It was based on the 3-door liftback [[Toyota Celica#First generation / A20/35 Series (1970\u20131977)|first generation Toyota Celica GT]].<ref name=\"racing65-1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.racing65.com/greatracingcars/celica1.html |title=:::: GREAT RACING CARS :::: Toyota Celica LB Turbo Gr5 Page 1 of 2 |publisher=Racing65.com |date=1977-07-30 |accessdate=2010-09-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715142147/http://www.racing65.com/greatracingcars/celica1.html |archivedate=2011-07-15 }}</ref>\n\nAs with all Group 5 cars, the Celica received extensive modifications to the bodywork, which was re-styled and built from lightweight [[glass-reinforced plastic|fiberglass]]. Only the hood, roof, doors and rail panel were retained from the stock model.<ref name=\"racing65-1\"/> The Celica's distinctive features are its wider body sills in front of and behind the door panel and sloping nose beyond the bonnet, which encases the double headlamps and square grille.<ref name=\"racing65-1\"/>\n\nTo keep up with its competitions, Schnitzer used the [[Toyota R engine#18R-G|Toyota 18R-G engine]]<ref name=TC1>[http://www.3sgte.com/page_27.htm ''Toyota Twin Cam''], p. 25</ref> from its production model with a specially designed 16 valve [[cylinder head]] and a [[Kugelfischer]] [[fuel injection]] system topped up with a KKK turbocharger.<ref name=\"racing65-1\"/> The engine produced a total output of {{convert|560|hp|0|abbr=on}} from its [[bore (engine)|bored]] {{convert|2090|cc|cuin|1|abbr=on}} engine.<ref name=\"racing65-1\"/>\n\nPartway through the 1978 season, as the Celica color scheme was changed from blue to red and white, revisions were also made to its bodywork to improve its [[aerodynamics]].<ref name=\"racing65-2\"/>\n\nAside being [[factory-backed|factory supported]], sponsorship was provided by optical manufacturer [[Rodenstock GmbH|Rodenstock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grandprixinsider.wordpress.com/2007/12/22/oh-those-germans/ |title=Oh, those Germans, part 3 \u2013 a Bavarian Jap |publisher=Grandprixinsider.wordpress.com |date=2007-12-22 |accessdate=2010-09-19}}</ref>\n\n==1977==\nThe Celica made its debut in the eighth round of the DRM series in [[Hockenheimring]] in July 1977, supporting the [[1977 German Grand Prix|German Grand Prix]]. Driven by [[Harald Ertl]], the blue Celica qualified thirteenth, 25 seconds per lap slower than the pole-winning 935.<ref name=\"speedhunters\"/> It retired from the race after four laps.<ref name=\"wspr-drm1977\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wspr-racing.com/wspr/results/drm/drm1977.html |title=DRM Hockenheim - Division I |accessdate=2010-09-27 |publisher=wspr-racing.com}}</ref> It returned for the following round in [[Circuit Zolder|Zolder]], qualifying seventh, five seconds slower than the pole-winning 935.<ref name=\"speedhunters\">{{cite web |url=http://speedhunters.com/archive/2009/02/19/retrospective-gt-gt-bigger-than-life-the-schnitzer-celica-turbo.aspx |title=Retrospective>>Bigger Than Life: The Schnitzer Celica |publisher=Speedhunters |date=2009-02-19 |accessdate=2010-09-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110119170131/http://speedhunters.com/archive/2009/02/19/retrospective-gt-gt-bigger-than-life-the-schnitzer-celica-turbo.aspx |archivedate=2011-01-19 }}</ref> There it retired after 3 laps. At the final round in [[N\u00fcrburgring]], it finished fourth behind three [[privateer (motorsport)|privateer]] Porsche 935s which it had intended to compete against.<ref name=\"wspr-drm1977\"/>\n\nThe Celica returned to Zolder for a non-championship ADAC Trophy to score its only victory.<ref name=\"racing65-1\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Darren Galpin |url=http://www.teamdan.com/archive/www2/miscsc/miscsc.html |title=Miscellaneous Sports Car Races |publisher=Teamdan.com |date= |accessdate=2010-09-19}}</ref>\n\n==1978==\nIn the 1978 season, [[Rolf Stommelen]], the defending champion with the Gelo Racing Team, a top Porsche privateer,<ref name=\"wspr-drm1977\"/><ref name=\"racing65-2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.racing65.com/greatracingcars/celica2.html |title=:::: GREAT RACING CARS :::: Toyota Celica LB Turbo Gr5 Page 2 of 2 |publisher=Racing65.com |accessdate=2010-09-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715142443/http://www.racing65.com/greatracingcars/celica2.html |archivedate=2011-07-15 }}</ref> took over driving duties from Ertl, who stepped down to campaign [[BMW]]s with the team in the lower Division 2.<ref name=\"wspr-drm1978\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wspr-racing.com/wspr/results/drm/drm1978.html |title=DRM Zolder - Division I |accessdate=2010-09-27 |publisher=wspr-racing.com}}</ref><ref name=\"racing65-2\"/> At the first round in Zolder, the Celica retired from engine failure on its second lap. At the [[N\u00fcrburgring]] round supporting the [[Eifelrennen]] skipping the previous round also at the same track, it retired after four laps.<ref name=\"wspr-drm1978\"/> Skipping the next round at [[AVUS]] to prepare for the [[1000 km N\u00fcrburgring]], Stommelen partnered with Ertl. Although they qualified sixth, the pair retired with water pump and engine failure. Returning for the following round at [[Mainz Finthen Airport|Mainz Finthen]], they finished eighth behind seven 935s (the highest finishing non-935 in the race).<ref name=\"wspr-drm1978\"/> At Hockenheim, after avoiding the previous two rounds, it retired after an accident on the seventh lap, and at Zolder, it retired failing to complete a single lap. It never returned to compete again with two rounds remaining.<ref name=\"wspr-drm1978\"/>\n\nAfter that season, Schnitzer exclusively campaigned BMWs with greater successes.<ref name=\"speedhunters\"/>\n\n==Japan==\nIn 1979, the Celica was brought over to [[Japan]] by [[TOM'S]] to compete in the Fuji Super Silhouette Series by its company founder, [[Nobuhide Tachi]]. In four of the five rounds held at [[Fuji Speedway]] he competed in, he won on its third attempt,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3070&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref> only to retire on all others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3059&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3057&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3056&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref>\n\nRetired in favour of their RA40 Celica that was developed in conjunction with [[Dome (constructor)|Dome]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dome.co.jp/museum/car_m/11_celica_turbo.html |title=Museum &#124;&#124; Car Museum |publisher=DOME |accessdate=2015-11-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930022006/http://www.dome.co.jp/museum/car_m/11_celica_turbo.html |archivedate=2012-09-30 }}</ref> the car was later sold to [[GReddy|Trust Japan]] in 1981, which then later reverted the front nose back to the original Schnitzer version configuration.<ref name=\"7tune\">{{cite web |url=http://www.7tune.com/abandoned-in-japan-the-schnitzer-gr5-celica/ |title=Abandoned In Japan: The Schnitzer Group 5 Celica |last=Zillin |first=Adam |publisher=7Tune.com |date=2009-08-09 |accessdate=2010-09-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826101013/http://www.7tune.com/abandoned-in-japan-the-schnitzer-gr5-celica/ |archivedate=2010-08-26 }}</ref> Under Kaoru Hoshino, it retired on its first round at Fuji,<ref name=\"jaf.or.jp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3069&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref> then finished ninth, six laps behind the winning Nissan Bluebird of Haruto Yanagida.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3087&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref> Subsequently it finished third<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3068&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref> and then eighth.<ref name=\"jaf.or.jp\"/>\n\nIn 1982, Hoshino retired in his next two races with the car after five<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3071&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref> and four laps respectively at Fuji.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3074&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref> In its final round at [[Tsukuba Circuit]], driven by Tatsuhiko Kaneumi, it finished fifth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3077&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref> The following year, the Schnitzer Celica was retired in favour of the newly acquired [[Porsche 956]] to compete in the newly introduced [[All Japan Sports Prototype Championship|All Japan Endurance Championship]].<ref name=\"7tune\"/> The Celica resurfaced again for its final appearance again at the same final round at Tsukuba, managing to finish ninth.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nSince the car was sold off, prior to the collapse of the super silhouette series in 1984, very little is known of its history. Nothing was heard of the car until it was discovered in the 2000s in a [[Wreck yard|junkyard]] in Japan in a neglected state with its Trust color scheme.<ref name=\"7tune\"/>\n\n==Models==\nDespite its limited success in the series in spite of its claim it \"won the German National Championship in 1977\" printed on its catalogue and its subsequent editions,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tamiyapedia.com/index.php?title=58009_Toyota_Celica_LB_Turbo |title=58009 Toyota Celica LB Turbo |work=Tamiyapedia |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130630144801/http://tamiyapedia.com/index.php?title=58009_Toyota_Celica_LB_Turbo |archive-date=2013-06-30}}</ref> the DRM liftback was immortalised in several different versions.\n\n[[Tamiya Corporation|Tamiya]] released static plastic model kits in both 1/20 and 1/24 scale,<ref name=\"racing65-2\"/><ref name=\"speedhunters\"/> and the 1/24 version was re-released several times until the late 2000s.\n\nTamiya also produced two different [[radio controlled car]] kits. The initial 1/12 scale version was released in 1977,<ref>{{citeweb|author=Chris Aldridge |url=http://www.tamiyaclub.com/car.asp?id=9 |title=Tamiya Toyota Celica LB Turbo, Vintage Tamiya Radio Control Cars through to Modern Tamiya R/C - Toyota Celica LB Turbo |publisher=Tamiyaclub.com |date= |accessdate=2010-09-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426043356/http://www.tamiyaclub.com/car.asp?id=9 |archive-date=2016-04-26}}</ref> followed by a bigger 1/10 scale version with polycarbonate body in 2012.\n\nBburago made a 1/24 scale toy model with metal body.\n\nIn 2003, slotcar manufacturer MRRC produced a 1/32 scale slotcar in different liveries, including a black colored fantasy \"GSR\" livery as a promotional item for the spanish Guia Slot Racing Magazine.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Toyota Sportscar Racers}}\n\n[[Category:Grand tourer racing cars]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Le Mans race cars]]\n[[Category:Toyota vehicles|Celica LB Turbo]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox racing car\n| Car_name = Toyota Celica LB Turbo\n| Image = \n| Category = [[Group 5 (racing)|Group 5]] [[sportscar racing|sportscar racer]]\n| Constructor = [[Toyota]]\n| Designer = \n| Team = [[Schnitzer Motorsport]]<br>[[TOM'S]]<br>[[GReddy|Trust Japan]]\n| Drivers = [[Harald Ertl]]<br>[[Rolf Stommelen]]<br>[[Nobuhide Tachi]]<br>Kaoru Hoshino<br>Tatsuhiko Kaneumi\n| Technical ref = <!-- <ref name=tech>Insert formatted reference</ref> -->\n| Chassis = \n| Rear suspension = \n| Front suspension = \n| Length = <!-- Use: {{convert|XXX|in|cm|1|abbr=on}} -->\n| Width = <!-- Use: {{convert|XXX|in|cm|1|abbr=on}} -->\n| Height = <!-- Use: {{convert|XXX|in|cm|1|abbr=on}} -->\n| Wheelbase = {{convert|95.3|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| Track = <!-- Use: {{convert|XXX|in|cm|1|abbr=on}} -->\n| Engine name = [[Toyota R engine#18R-G|Toyota 18R-G]]\n| Capacity = {{convert|2090|cc|cuin|1|abbr=on}}\n| Configuration = [[Inline-four engine|I4]]\n| Turbo/NA = [[Turbocharger]]\n| Engine position = [[Front-engine design|Front-engine]]d, [[longitudinal engine|longitudinally mounted]]\n| Gearbox name = \n| Gears = 5-speed\n| Type = [[manual transmission]]\n| Differential = \n| Weight = {{convert|860|kg|lb|1|abbr=on}}\n| Fuel = [[Royal Dutch Shell|Shell]]\n| Tyres = [[Dunlop Rubber|Dunlop]]\n| Debut = 1977 DRM Hockenheim\n| Races = 21\n| Wins = 2\n| Cons_champ = \n| Drivers_champ = \n| Teams_champ = \n| Poles = \n| Fastest_laps = \n}}\nThe '''Toyota Celica LB Turbo''' was a [[Group 5 (racing)|Group 5 Special Production]] [[racecar]] version of the 3-door liftback [[Toyota Celica#First generation / A20/35 Series (1970\u20131977)|first generation Toyota Celica 2000 GT]] built by [[Schnitzer Motorsport|Schnitzer]] via [[Toyota]] Deutschland to compete in Division 1 of the [[Deutsche Rennsport Meisterschaft|DRM]].\n\nIt competed in the [[Germany|German]] series in 1977 and 1978. Plagued by reliability problems, it finished twice and won a non-championship race. At the end of its [[Europe]]an career, it went on to compete in [[Japan]] with minor success.\n\nThroughout its competitive seasons, it was the only non-German car to compete in the top division of the German series.<ref name=\"wspr-drm1977\" /><ref name=\"wspr-drm1978\" />\n\n==Development==\nThe A20 Celica was built to compete against the [[Porsche 935]]s that had dominated international [[motorsport]] and also the Division 1 of the German DRM series for Group 5 cars. It was based on the 3-door liftback [[Toyota Celica#First generation / A20/35 Series (1970\u20131977)|first generation Toyota Celica 2000 GT]].<ref name=\"racing65-1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.racing65.com/greatracingcars/celica1.html |title=:::: GREAT RACING CARS :::: Toyota Celica LB Turbo Gr5 Page 1 of 2 |publisher=Racing65.com |date=1977-07-30 |accessdate=2010-09-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715142147/http://www.racing65.com/greatracingcars/celica1.html |archivedate=2011-07-15 }}</ref>\n\nAs with all Group 5 cars, the Celica received extensive modifications to the bodywork, which was re-styled and built from lightweight [[glass-reinforced plastic|fiberglass]]. Only the hood, roof, doors and rail panel were retained from the stock model.<ref name=\"racing65-1\"/> The Celica's distinctive features are its wider body sills in front of and behind the door panel and sloping nose beyond the bonnet, which encases the double headlamps and square grille.<ref name=\"racing65-1\"/>\n\nTo keep up with its competitions, Schnitzer used the [[Toyota R engine#18R-G|Toyota 18R-G engine]]<ref name=TC1>[http://www.3sgte.com/page_27.htm ''Toyota Twin Cam''], p. 25</ref> from its production model with a specially designed 16 valve [[cylinder head]] and a [[Kugelfischer]] [[fuel injection]] system topped up with a KKK turbocharger.<ref name=\"racing65-1\"/> The engine produced a total output of {{convert|560|hp|0|abbr=on}} from its [[bore (engine)|bored]] {{convert|2090|cc|cuin|1|abbr=on}} engine.<ref name=\"racing65-1\"/>\n\nPartway through the 1978 season, as the Celica color scheme was changed from blue to red and white, revisions were also made to its bodywork to improve its [[aerodynamics]].<ref name=\"racing65-2\"/>\n\nAside being [[factory-backed|factory supported]], sponsorship was provided by optical manufacturer [[Rodenstock GmbH|Rodenstock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grandprixinsider.wordpress.com/2007/12/22/oh-those-germans/ |title=Oh, those Germans, part 3 \u2013 a Bavarian Jap |publisher=Grandprixinsider.wordpress.com |date=2007-12-22 |accessdate=2010-09-19}}</ref>\n\n==1977==\nThe Celica made its debut in the eighth round of the DRM series in [[Hockenheimring]] in July 1977, supporting the [[1977 German Grand Prix|German Grand Prix]]. Driven by [[Harald Ertl]], the blue Celica qualified thirteenth, 25 seconds per lap slower than the pole-winning 935.<ref name=\"speedhunters\"/> It retired from the race after four laps.<ref name=\"wspr-drm1977\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wspr-racing.com/wspr/results/drm/drm1977.html |title=DRM Hockenheim - Division I |accessdate=2010-09-27 |publisher=wspr-racing.com}}</ref> It returned for the following round in [[Circuit Zolder|Zolder]], qualifying seventh, five seconds slower than the pole-winning 935.<ref name=\"speedhunters\">{{cite web |url=http://speedhunters.com/archive/2009/02/19/retrospective-gt-gt-bigger-than-life-the-schnitzer-celica-turbo.aspx |title=Retrospective>>Bigger Than Life: The Schnitzer Celica |publisher=Speedhunters |date=2009-02-19 |accessdate=2010-09-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110119170131/http://speedhunters.com/archive/2009/02/19/retrospective-gt-gt-bigger-than-life-the-schnitzer-celica-turbo.aspx |archivedate=2011-01-19 }}</ref> There it retired after 3 laps. At the final round in [[N\u00fcrburgring]], it finished fourth behind three [[privateer (motorsport)|privateer]] Porsche 935s which it had intended to compete against.<ref name=\"wspr-drm1977\"/>\n\nThe Celica returned to Zolder for a non-championship ADAC Trophy to score its only victory.<ref name=\"racing65-1\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Darren Galpin |url=http://www.teamdan.com/archive/www2/miscsc/miscsc.html |title=Miscellaneous Sports Car Races |publisher=Teamdan.com |date= |accessdate=2010-09-19}}</ref>\n\n==1978==\nIn the 1978 season, [[Rolf Stommelen]], the defending champion with the Gelo Racing Team, a top Porsche privateer,<ref name=\"wspr-drm1977\"/><ref name=\"racing65-2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.racing65.com/greatracingcars/celica2.html |title=:::: GREAT RACING CARS :::: Toyota Celica LB Turbo Gr5 Page 2 of 2 |publisher=Racing65.com |accessdate=2010-09-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715142443/http://www.racing65.com/greatracingcars/celica2.html |archivedate=2011-07-15 }}</ref> took over driving duties from Ertl, who stepped down to campaign [[BMW]]s with the team in the lower Division 2.<ref name=\"wspr-drm1978\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wspr-racing.com/wspr/results/drm/drm1978.html |title=DRM Zolder - Division I |accessdate=2010-09-27 |publisher=wspr-racing.com}}</ref><ref name=\"racing65-2\"/> At the first round in Zolder, the Celica retired from engine failure on its second lap. At the [[N\u00fcrburgring]] round supporting the [[Eifelrennen]] skipping the previous round also at the same track, it retired after four laps.<ref name=\"wspr-drm1978\"/> Skipping the next round at [[AVUS]] to prepare for the [[1000 km N\u00fcrburgring]], Stommelen partnered with Ertl. Although they qualified sixth, the pair retired with water pump and engine failure. Returning for the following round at [[Mainz Finthen Airport|Mainz Finthen]], they finished eighth behind seven 935s (the highest finishing non-935 in the race).<ref name=\"wspr-drm1978\"/> At Hockenheim, after avoiding the previous two rounds, it retired after an accident on the seventh lap, and at Zolder, it retired failing to complete a single lap. It never returned to compete again with two rounds remaining.<ref name=\"wspr-drm1978\"/>\n\nAfter that season, Schnitzer exclusively campaigned BMWs with greater successes.<ref name=\"speedhunters\"/>\n\n==Japan==\nIn 1979, the Celica was brought over to [[Japan]] by [[TOM'S]] to compete in the Fuji Super Silhouette Series by its company founder, [[Nobuhide Tachi]]. In four of the five rounds held at [[Fuji Speedway]] he competed in, he won on its third attempt,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3070&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref> only to retire on all others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3059&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3057&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3056&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref>\n\nRetired in favour of their RA40 Celica that was developed in conjunction with [[Dome (constructor)|Dome]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dome.co.jp/museum/car_m/11_celica_turbo.html |title=Museum &#124;&#124; Car Museum |publisher=DOME |accessdate=2015-11-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930022006/http://www.dome.co.jp/museum/car_m/11_celica_turbo.html |archivedate=2012-09-30 }}</ref> the car was later sold to [[GReddy|Trust Japan]] in 1981, which then later reverted the front nose back to the original Schnitzer version configuration.<ref name=\"7tune\">{{cite web |url=http://www.7tune.com/abandoned-in-japan-the-schnitzer-gr5-celica/ |title=Abandoned In Japan: The Schnitzer Group 5 Celica |last=Zillin |first=Adam |publisher=7Tune.com |date=2009-08-09 |accessdate=2010-09-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826101013/http://www.7tune.com/abandoned-in-japan-the-schnitzer-gr5-celica/ |archivedate=2010-08-26 }}</ref> Under Kaoru Hoshino, it retired on its first round at Fuji,<ref name=\"jaf.or.jp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3069&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref> then finished ninth, six laps behind the winning Nissan Bluebird of Haruto Yanagida.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3087&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref> Subsequently it finished third<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3068&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref> and then eighth.<ref name=\"jaf.or.jp\"/>\n\nIn 1982, Hoshino retired in his next two races with the car after five<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3071&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref> and four laps respectively at Fuji.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3074&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref> In its final round at [[Tsukuba Circuit]], driven by Tatsuhiko Kaneumi, it finished fifth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaf.or.jp/CGI/msports/results/n-race/detail-result.cgi?race_id=3077&window_flg=1 |title=\u5927\u4f1a\u7d50\u679c |publisher=Jaf.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref> The following year, the Schnitzer Celica was retired in favour of the newly acquired [[Porsche 956]] to compete in the newly introduced [[All Japan Sports Prototype Championship|All Japan Endurance Championship]].<ref name=\"7tune\"/> The Celica resurfaced again for its final appearance again at the same final round at Tsukuba, managing to finish ninth.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nSince the car was sold off, prior to the collapse of the super silhouette series in 1984, very little is known of its history. Nothing was heard of the car until it was discovered in the 2000s in a [[Wreck yard|junkyard]] in Japan in a neglected state with its Trust color scheme.<ref name=\"7tune\"/>\n\n==Models==\nDespite its limited success in the series in spite of its claim it \"won the German National Championship in 1977\" printed on its catalogue and its subsequent editions,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tamiyapedia.com/index.php?title=58009_Toyota_Celica_LB_Turbo |title=58009 Toyota Celica LB Turbo |work=Tamiyapedia |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130630144801/http://tamiyapedia.com/index.php?title=58009_Toyota_Celica_LB_Turbo |archive-date=2013-06-30}}</ref> the DRM liftback was immortalised in several different versions.\n\n[[Tamiya Corporation|Tamiya]] released static plastic model kits in both 1/20 and 1/24 scale,<ref name=\"racing65-2\"/><ref name=\"speedhunters\"/> and the 1/24 version was re-released several times until the late 2000s.\n\nTamiya also produced two different [[radio controlled car]] kits. The initial 1/12 scale version was released in 1977,<ref>{{citeweb|author=Chris Aldridge |url=http://www.tamiyaclub.com/car.asp?id=9 |title=Tamiya Toyota Celica LB Turbo, Vintage Tamiya Radio Control Cars through to Modern Tamiya R/C - Toyota Celica LB Turbo |publisher=Tamiyaclub.com |date= |accessdate=2010-09-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426043356/http://www.tamiyaclub.com/car.asp?id=9 |archive-date=2016-04-26}}</ref> followed by a bigger 1/10 scale version with polycarbonate body in 2012.\n\nBburago made a 1/24 scale toy model with metal body.\n\nIn 2003, slotcar manufacturer MRRC produced a 1/32 scale slotcar in different liveries, including a black colored fantasy \"GSR\" livery as a promotional item for the spanish Guia Slot Racing Magazine.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Toyota Sportscar Racers}}\n\n[[Category:Grand tourer racing cars]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Le Mans race cars]]\n[[Category:Toyota vehicles|Celica LB Turbo]]\n", "name_user": "HotWheels53", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toyota_Celica_LB_Turbo"}
{"title_page": "Gretchen Whitmer", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{short description|49th Governor of Michigan}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Gretchen Whitmer\n| order = 49th [[Governor of Michigan]]\n| lieutenant = [[Garlin Gilchrist]]\n| term_start = January 1, 2019\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Rick Snyder]]\n| successor = \n| image = Gov. Gretchen Whitmer (cropped).jpg\n| office1 = [[Ingham County, Michigan|Ingham County]] [[Prosecutor]]\n| term_start1 = July 21, 2016\n| term_end1 = December 31, 2016\n| predecessor1 = [[Stuart Dunnings III]]\n| successor1 = Carol Siemon\n| office2 = [[Minority leader|Minority Leader]] of the [[Michigan Senate]]\n| deputy2 = [[Steve Bieda]]\n| term_start2 = January 1, 2011\n| term_end2 = January 1, 2015\n| predecessor2 = [[Mike Prusi]]\n| successor2 = [[Jim Ananich]]\n| state_senate3 = Michigan\n| district3 = 23rd\n| term_start3 = March 21, 2006\n| term_end3 = January 1, 2015\n| predecessor3 = [[Virgil Bernero]]\n| successor3 = [[Curtis Hertel Jr.]]\n| office4 = Member of the <br>[[Michigan House of Representatives]]\n| term_start4 = January 1, 2001\n| term_end4 = March 21, 2006\n| predecessor4 = [[Laura Baird]]\n| successor4 = [[Mark Meadows (Michigan politician)|Mark Meadows]]\n| constituency4 = 70th district (2001\u20132003)<br>69th district (2003\u20132006)\n| birth_name = Gretchen Esther Whitmer\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1971|8|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Lansing, Michigan|Lansing]], [[Michigan]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse = Gary Shrewsbury (div.)<br>{{marriage|Marc Mallory|2011}}\n| children = 2\n| residence = [[Michigan Governor's Mansion|Governor's Mansion]]\n| education = [[Michigan State University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| website = {{url|michigan.gov/gov|Government website}}\n| signature = Whitmersig.jpg\n}}\n'''Gretchen Esther Whitmer''' (born August 23, 1971) is an American politician serving as the [[List of Governors of Michigan|49th]] [[governor of Michigan]]. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], she served in the [[Michigan House of Representatives]] from 2001 to 2006 and in the [[Michigan Senate]] from 2006 to 2015. \n\nBorn and raised in [[Michigan]] as the daughter of two lawyers, Whitmer graduated from [[Forest Hills Central High School]] near [[Grand Rapids, Michigan|Grand Rapids]], [[Michigan State University]], and the [[Michigan State University College of Law]]. She ran unsuccessfully for the state house in the 1990s before being elected in 2000. In 2006 she became a state senator, a position she kept until [[term limit|term limits]] forced her to step down in 2015. She was the Senate's first female Democratic leader from 2011 to 2015. In 2013, Whitmer gained national attention for a floor speech during a debate on [[abortion]] in which she shared her experience of being [[Sexual Assault|sexually assaulted]]. For six months in 2016, she was the [[prosecutor|county prosecutor]] for [[Ingham County, Michigan|Ingham County]].\n\nWhitmer was elected governor in [[2018 Michigan gubernatorial election|the 2018 gubernatorial election]], defeating Republican [[Attorney General of Michigan|Attorney General]] [[Bill Schuette]]. As governor, Whitmer has focused on healthcare and infrastructure, which now appears she was a failure at and wasted tens of millions of dollars in fsiled preperations for emergency pandemics. In February 2020, she was selected to give [[Response to the State of the Union address|the Democratic response]] to [[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump|Donald Trump's]] [[2020 State of the Union Address]]. She is the national co-chairwoman of the [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nGretchen Whitmer was born in 1971 in [[Lansing, Michigan]], as the eldest of three children to Sharon H. \"Sherry\" Reisig and Richard Whitmer, who were both lawyers.<ref name=\"LegalNews\">{{cite web|title=Monday Profile: Gretchen Whitmer|url=http://www.oaklandlegalnews.com/washtenaw/1423164|website=LegalNews.com|accessdate=March 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/name/sharon-whitmer-obituary?pid=182956096|title=SHARON WHITMER Obituary - Detroit, Michigan &#124; Legacy.com}}</ref> Her father served as head of the state's Department of Commerce under Governor [[William Milliken]] and was the president and [[CEO]] of [[Blue Cross Blue Shield of Michigan]] between 1988 and 2006.<ref name=\"CRAIN18\">{{cite news |title=Blue Cross takes punches in governor's race |url=http://www.crainsdetroit.com/article/20180708/news/665536/blue-cross-takes-punches-in-governors-race |accessdate=July 11, 2018 |work=[[Crain's Detroit Business]] |date=July 8, 2018}}</ref> Whitmer's mother worked as an assistant attorney general under [[Michigan Attorney General]] [[Frank J. Kelley|Frank Kelley]].<ref name=\"csgmidwest\">{{cite web|title=Stateline Profile Gretchen Whitmer|url=http://www.csgmidwest.org/publications/documents/p8Whitmer.pdf|website=csgmidwest.org/|accessdate=March 2, 2017}}</ref> Her parents divorced when she was 10 years old; she and her siblings moved with their mother to [[Grand Rapids, Michigan|Grand Rapids]]. Her father traveled from his home in Detroit to visit the family at least once a week.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/2018/05/24/gretchen-whitmer-governor-michigan/629845002/|title=Gretchen Whitmer's perplexing problem in race for Michigan governor|work=Detroit Free Press|accessdate=August 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhitmer graduated from [[Forest Hills Central High School]], just outside Grand Rapids.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mathews|first1=Reena|title=FHC alumna Senator Gretchen Whitmer is running for Governor|url=http://thecentraltrend.com/13375/showcase/senator-gretchen-whitmer-fhc-alumna-running-for-governor/|accessdate=March 2, 2017|work=The Central Trend|date=January 17, 2017}}</ref> She earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in communications from [[Michigan State University]] in 1993 and a [[Juris Doctor]] from [[Michigan State University College of Law|Detroit College of Law at Michigan State University]] in 1998.\n\n==State Legislature==\n===House of Representatives===\nWhitmer originally ran for the [[Michigan House of Representatives]] in the 1990s but was unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jilani |first1=Zaid |title=A Blue Cross CEO Encouraged a Michigan Woman to Get Into Politics. Now She\u2019s Running for Governor and Says Single Payer Is Unrealistic. |url=https://theintercept.com/2018/07/18/michigan-governor-race-gretchen-whitmer-blue-cross/ |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |publisher=The Intercept |date=18 July 2018}}</ref> In 2000, she tried again and was elected to represent the 23rd legislative district. She was reelected in 2002 and 2004.<ref name=MichManual>{{cite book | author = Michigan Legislative Service Bureau | title = Michigan Manual 2005\u20132006 | publisher = Legislative Council, State of Michigan | year = 2006 | location = Lansing | url = https://archive.org/details/michiganmanual00mich/page/129 | isbn = 1-878210-06-8 | accessdate = June 29, 2007 | page = [https://archive.org/details/michiganmanual00mich/page/129 129] | url-access = registration }}</ref>\n\n===State Senate===\nIn March 2006, Whitmer left the state house and became a [[Michigan State Senate|State Senator]]. She was elected and reelected in 2006 and 2010. In 2011, Whitmer's Democratic colleagues unanimously chose her to be the Senate Democratic Leader, making her the first woman to lead a party caucus in the Senate. She continued in that role for the remainder of her time there.<ref name=\"csgmidwest\" /> Due to [[term limit|term limits]], Whitmer was unable to run for reelection in 2014 and left office in 2015.<ref name=SenateDem>{{cite web|author=Michigan Senate Democrats |title=Michigan Senate Democrats: About Gretchen Whitmer |year=2007 |url=http://www.senate.mi.gov/whitmer/about.htm |accessdate=June 29, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070205183624/http://www.senate.mi.gov/whitmer/about.htm |archivedate=February 5, 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> In 2013, she received national recognition when she discussed her experience of being [[Sexual Assault|sexually assaulted]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Mitch |title=Who Is Gov. Gretchen Whitmer of Michigan, the Democrats\u2019 Answer to Trump? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/04/us/politics/gretchen-whitmer-state-of-the-union.html |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |publisher=The New York Times |date=4 February 2020}}</ref> She told the story during a debate about [[abortion]] rights, particularly for victims of [[rape]], arguing victims should be allowed to terminate pregnancies which resulted from rape.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Abbey-Lambertz |first1=Kate |title=Lawmaker Bravely Reveals She Was Victim Of Rape In Emotional 'Abortion Insurance' Debate |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/gretchen-whitmer-rape_n_4432203 |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |publisher=The Huffington Post |date=December 12, 2013 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Ingham County Prosecutor==\nOn May 11, 2016, it was announced that the judges of Michigan's 30th Judicial Circuit Court had unanimously selected Whitmer to serve the remaining six months of the term of outgoing Ingham County Prosecutor Stuart Dunnings III<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lansingstatejournal.com/story/news/local/capitol/2016/05/11/whitmer-chosen-interim-ingham-county-prosecutor/84248374/ |title=Whitmer chosen for interim Ingham County prosecutor |work=Lansing State Journal |author=Justin A. Hicks |date=May 11, 2016}}</ref> after he was arrested on March 14, 2016, and charged with 11 counts of involvement with a prostitute and four counts of willful neglect of duty.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/index.ssf/2016/03/ingham_county_prosecutor_alleg.html |title=Ingham County Prosecutor allegedly engaged prostitutes 'hundreds of times' |work=MLive Media Group |author=Emily Lawler |date=March 14, 2016 |accessdate=May 11, 2016}}</ref> In a letter dated March 29, 2016, Dunnings announced he would resign effective July 2.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/jackson/index.ssf/2016/03/stuart_dunnings_informs_ingham.html |title=Stuart Dunnings informs Ingham County he is resigning as prosecutor |work=Jackson Citizen Patriot |author=Benjamin Raven |date=March 29, 2016 |accessdate=May 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn June 21, 2016, Whitmer was administered the oath of office as prosecutor by Ingham County Circuit Court Chief Judge Janelle Lawless. She said her top priorities during her six months of service would be to determine if any other officials in the prosecutor's office knew about Dunnings's alleged crimes and to change how the office handled domestic violence and sexual assault cases.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lansingstatejournal.com/story/news/local/2016/06/21/whitmer-looking-forward-starting-prosecutor/86139690/ |title=Whitmer 'looking forward' to starting as prosecutor |authors=Matt Mencarini and Justin A. Hinkley |work=Lansing State Journal |date=June 22, 2016 |accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 22, 2016, Whitmer issued an 11-page report on whether Dunnings's alleged criminal activity had affected cases handled by the office. The report concluded that employees \"were never asked to compromise a case or look the other way\" and that she had \"...full confidence that any problem that had existed in this office left with Mr. Dunnings.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lansingstatejournal.com/story/news/local/watchdog/2016/07/22/problems-left-mr-dunnings-whitmer-says/87431782/ |title=Cases unaffected by Dunnings' alleged crimes, Whitmer says |author=Justin A. Hinkley |work=Lansing State Journal |date=July 22, 2016 |accessdate=August 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://pa.ingham.org/Portals/PA/Documents/Report%20on%20the%20Status%20of%20the%20Ingham%20County%20Prosecutor's%20Office.pdf |title=Report on the Status of the Ingham County Prosecutor's Office |publisher=Ingham County Prosecutor's Office |first=Gretchen |last=Whitmer |date=July 22, 2016 |accessdate=August 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160803145021/http://pa.ingham.org/Portals/PA/Documents/Report%20on%20the%20Status%20of%20the%20Ingham%20County%20Prosecutor's%20Office.pdf |archive-date=August 3, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Whitmer's term expired on December 31, 2016.\n\n==Governorship==\n[[File:Michigan National Guard members participate in inauguration, Adjutant General swearing-in 190101-F-VX133-049.jpg|thumb|Whitmer speaking at a National Guard ceremony in January 2019]]\n\n===2018 election===\nOn January 3, 2017, Whitmer announced she would run in the [[Michigan gubernatorial election, 2018|2018 Michigan gubernatorial race]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Whitmer|first1=Gretchen|title=I'm ready \u2014 are you?|url=https://medium.com/@gretchenwhitmer_12225/im-ready-are-you-c150e9f75e97|website=Medium|accessdate=June 3, 2017|date=January 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn August 7, 2018, Whitmer became the Democratic nominee for governor of Michigan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/07/us/politics/gretchen-whitmer-michigan-election-results.html|title=Whitmer and Schuette Win Michigan Governor's Nominations|website=nytimes.com|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref> She won all 83 counties in the state in the Democratic primary<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://miboecfr.nictusa.com/election/results/2018PRI_CENR.html/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=August 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180809220343/https://miboecfr.nictusa.com/election/results/2018PRI_CENR.html |archive-date=August 9, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>.  \n\nIn July 2018, Republican officials accused Whitmer of supporting the movement to [[Abolish ICE|abolish]] [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement|ICE]], a claim Whitmer disputed. She said that if elected she would focus on improving Michigan's \"fundamentals\", such as schools, roads, and water systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/74dead3614e346e495e064c3e42a6f13|title=AP Interview: Whitmer focuses on 'fundamentals' like roads|date=September 15, 2018|website=apnews.com|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhitmer's main opponent was Republican [[Bill Schuette]], the term-limited [[Michigan Attorney General|Attorney General of Michigan]]. The two candidates met for a debate on October 12, 2018, in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan|Grand Rapids]] at [[WOOD-TV]]. A second debate was held at [[WDIV-TV|WDIV]] studios in Detroit on October 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlive.com/news/index.ssf/2018/10/gretchen_whitmer_bill_schuette.html|title=Gretchen Whitmer, Bill Schuette butt heads at first gubernatorial debate|website=mlive.com|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhitmer defeated Schuette in the November 6 election by nearly a 10-point margin.<ref>{{cite web |title=Michigan Election Results |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/11/06/us/elections/results-michigan-elections.html |website=New York Times |publisher=The Associated Press |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nWhitmer describes herself as a progressive Democrat<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Smith|first=Mitch|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/04/us/politics/gretchen-whitmer-state-of-the-union.html|title=Democrats Turn to Gov. Gretchen Whitmer of Michigan for Trump State of the Union Response|date=2020-02-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> who can work with state legislators from different political perspectives.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAs both a gubernatorial candidate and as governor, one of Whitmer's key pledges was to \"fix the damn roads\", a reference to Michigan's struggling infrastructure. But her initial post-election plan to fund road repairs with a 45-cent-per-gallon gas tax increase was deeply unpopular, with one poll finding it opposed by 75% of Michigan voters, including majorities of both Democrats and independents.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Livengood |first1=Chad |title=Poll: 75% oppose Whitmer's 45-cent gas tax hike plan |url=https://www.crainsdetroit.com/voices-chad-livengood/poll-75-oppose-whitmers-45-cent-gas-tax-hike-plan |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |work=Crain's Detroit Business |publisher=Crain Communications |date=April 18, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Even Democratic legislators in Michigan's Republican-controlled legislature largely declined to support the plan, which would have nearly tripled Michigan's gas tax and potentially made it the highest in the nation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Beggin |first1=Riley|title=Michigan House Dem leader says Whitmer\u2019s 45-cent gas tax is probably dead |url=https://www.bridgemi.com/michigan-government/michigan-house-dem-leader-says-whitmers-45-cent-gas-tax-probably-dead |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |work=Bridge Michigan |publisher=Center for Michigan |date=August 29, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news |last1=Malewitz|first1=Jim |last2=Wilkinson |first2=Mike |title=Gretchen Whitmer\u2019s plan to fix Michigan roads: Nearly triple gas tax |url=https://www.bridgemi.com/michigan-government/gretchen-whitmers-plan-fix-michigan-roads-nearly-triple-gas-tax |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |work=Bridge Michigan |publisher=Center for Michigan |date=March 4, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nWhitmer's first budget earmarked several billions of dollars for investment in infrastructure.<ref name=\"Highlights\">{{cite news|last1=CNN|first1=Devan Cole|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/04/politics/who-is-gretchen-whitmer-state-of-the-union-response/index.html|title=Michigan governor's response to Trump's State of the Union to highlight state Democrats want to win in 2020|date=February 4, 2020|accessdate=February 4, 2020|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Law |first1=Tara |title=Gretchen Whitmer Is Giving the Democrats' State of the Union Response. Here's What to Know |url=https://time.com/5777872/gretchen-whitmer-democratic-response-state-of-the-union/ |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |work=Time |publisher=TIME |date=February 4, 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Neavling |first1=Steve |title=Whitmer breaks pledge to 'fix the damn roads' under new budget |url=https://www.metrotimes.com/news-hits/archives/2019/09/09/whitmer-breaks-pledge-to-fix-the-damn-roads-under-new-budget |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |publisher=Detroit Metro Times |date=September 9, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> In 2019, she struggled with the Republican-controlled legislature to pass a budget and made several concessions.<ref name=\"Highlights\" />\n\nThe gubernatorial election and national conversation during Whitmer's time in office focused largely on healthcare. During the election, she was the only Democratic candidate not to support a [[single-payer healthcare]] system.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jilani |first1=Zaid |title=A Blue Cross CEO Encouraged a Michigan Woman to Get Into Politics. Now She\u2019s Running for Governor and Says Single Payer Is Unrealistic. |url=https://theintercept.com/2018/07/18/michigan-governor-race-gretchen-whitmer-blue-cross/ |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |publisher=The Intercept |date=July 18, 2018}}</ref> As governor, she has focused on women's healthcare and [[Medicaid]] expansion.<ref name=\"Highlights\"></ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Whitmer was selected to deliver the Democratic response to [[Donald Trump]]'s [[2020 State of the Union Address]]. Michigan is considered a [[swing state]] in the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 presidential election]], and it was speculated that Democrats hoped selecting Whitmer would bolster their chance of winning the state.<ref name=\"Highlights\"></ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lawler |first1=Emily |last2=Barrett |first2=Michael |title=5 things to know about Michigan Gov. Gretchen Whitmer as she takes the national stage |url=https://www.mlive.com/news/2020/02/5-things-to-know-about-michigan-gov-gretchen-whitmer-as-she-takes-the-national-stage.html |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |publisher=Michigan Live |date=4 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Mitch |title=Democrats Turn to Gov. Gretchen Whitmer of Michigan for Trump State of the Union Response |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/04/us/politics/gretchen-whitmer-state-of-the-union.html |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |publisher=The New York Times |date=February 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin |title=Michigan House of Representatives District 70 Democratic Primary, 2000<ref>{{cite web | url=http://miboecfr.nictusa.com/election/results/00pri/ | title=2000 Michigan Election Results | publisher=Michigan Department of State |date=September 28, 2016 |accessdate=September 26, 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n  | |party = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Gretchen Whitmer\n  |votes      = 2,434\n  |percentage = 47.4\n  |change     = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  | |party = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Mary Lindemann\n  |votes      = 2,152\n  |percentage = 41.9\n  |change     = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  | |party = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = John Schlinker\n  |votes      = 284\n  |percentage = 5.5\n  |change     = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  | |party = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Robert McCann\n  |votes      = 263\n  |percentage = 5.1\n  |change     = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n  | |votes = 281\n  |percentage = 5.5\n  |change     = N/A\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin |title=Michigan House of Representatives District 70 Election, 2000<ref>{{cite web | url=http://miboecfr.nictusa.com/election/results/00gen/#08070000 | title=2000 Michigan Election Results | publisher=Michigan Department of State |date=September 28, 2016 |accessdate=September 26, 2017}}</ref>}}}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n  | |party = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Gretchen Whitmer\n  |votes      = 17,409\n  |percentage = 56.6\n  |change     = -0.1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  | |party = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Bill Hollister\n  |votes      = 13,355\n  |percentage = 43.4\n  |change     = +3.6\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n  | |votes = 4,054\n  |percentage = 13.2\n  |change     = -3.7\n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n  | |votes = 30,764\n  |percentage = \n  |change     = +21.5\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link\n| |winner = Democratic Party (US)\n|swing = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin |title=Michigan House of Representatives District 69 Election, 2002<ref>{{cite web | url=http://miboecfr.nictusa.com/election/results/02GEN/#08069000 | title=2002 Michigan Election Results | publisher=Michigan Department of State |date=September 28, 2016 |accessdate=September 26, 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n  | |party = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Gretchen Whitmer\n  |votes      = 18,002\n  |percentage = 62.5\n  |change     = +5.9\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  | |party = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Larry Ward\n  |votes      = 10,783\n  |percentage = 37.5\n  |change     = -5.9\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n  | |votes = 7,219\n  |percentage = 25.0\n  |change     = -10.8\n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n  | |votes = 28,785\n  |percentage = \n  |change     = +12.9\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link\n| |winner = Democratic Party (US)\n|swing = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin |title=Michigan House of Representatives District 69 Election, 2004<ref>{{cite web | url=http://miboecfr.nictusa.com/election/results/04GEN/#08069000 | title=2004 Michigan Election Results | publisher=Michigan Department of State |date=September 28, 2016 |accessdate=September 26, 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n  | |party = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Gretchen Whitmer (I)\n  |votes      = 26,828\n  |percentage = 65.7\n  |change     = +3.2\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  | |party = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Angela Lindsay\n  |votes      = 14,307\n  |percentage = 34.3\n  |change     = -3.2\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n  | |votes = 12,521\n  |percentage = 31.4\n  |change     = +6.4\n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n  | |votes = 40,865\n  |percentage = \n  |change     = +42.0\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link\n| |winner = Democratic Party (US)\n|swing = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin |title=Michigan Senate District 23 Election, 2006}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n  | |party = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Gretchen Whitmer\n  |votes      = 64,404\n  |percentage = 69.8\n  |change     = +16.4\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  | |party = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Frank Lambert\n  |votes      = 27,931\n  |percentage = 30.2\n  |change     = +16.4\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n  | |votes = 36,473\n  |percentage = 39.5\n  |change     = +32.8\n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n  | |votes = 92,335\n  |percentage = 100\n  |change     = +11.6\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link\n| |winner = Democratic Party (US)\n|swing = +16.4\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin |title=Michigan State Senate District 23 Election, 2010}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n  | |party = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Gretchen Whitmer (Incumbent)\n  |votes      = 49,974\n  |percentage = 64.0\n  |change     = -5.8\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  | |party = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Kyle Haubrich\n  |votes      = 28,127\n  |percentage = 36.0\n  |change     = +5.8\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n  | |votes = 21,847\n  |percentage = 28.0\n  |change     = -11.6\n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n  | |votes = 78,101\n  |percentage = 100\n  |change     = -15.4\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link\n| |winner = Democratic Party (US)\n|swing = -5.8\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin|title=Michigan gubernatorial election, 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mielections.us/election/results/2018GEN_CENR.html|title=2018 Michigan Official General Election Results - 11/06/2018|website=mielections.us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lwvoa.org/files/LWVOAFullVoterGuideNovember2018-compressed.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=November 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116173304/http://www.lwvoa.org/files/LWVOAFullVoterGuideNovember2018-compressed.pdf |archive-date=November 16, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n |party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = Gretchen Whitmer<br>[[Garlin Gilchrist]]\n |votes = 2,256,791\n |percentage = 53.34%\n |change = +6.48%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party = Republican Party (United States)|candidate = [[Bill Schuette]]<br>[[Lisa Posthumus Lyons]]|votes = 1,853,650|percentage = 43.81%|change = -7.11%\n| }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party = Libertarian Party (United States)|candidate = Bill Gelineau <br>Angelique Chaiser Thomas|votes = 56,752|percentage = 1.34%|change = +0.21%\n| }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party = Green Party of the United States|candidate = Jennifer V. Kurland<br>Charin H. Davenport|votes = 28,857|percentage = 0.68%|change = +0.21%\n| }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party = Constitution Party (United States)|candidate = Todd Schleiger<br>Earl P. Lackie|votes = 24,701|percentage = 0.58%|change = -0.03%\n| }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party = Natural Law Party|candidate = Keith Butkovitch<br>Raymond Warner|votes = 10,258|percentage = 0.24%|change = -\n| }}\n{{Election box majority\n| |votes = 403,141\n |percentage = 9.53%\n |change = +5.47%\n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n| |votes = 4,231,009\n |percentage =\n |change = 34.04%\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link\n  | |winner = Democratic Party (US)\n  |loser = Republican Party (US)\n  |swing = \n}}\n{{election box end}}\n\n==Political positions==\n\n===Education===\nWhitmer would like to phase in full-day Universal Pre-K for 4-year-olds in Michigan. She also wants to reduce the cost of childcare for struggling families. She would eliminate Michigan's current 3rd grade \"read or flunk\" policy, which she has said penalizes students who have been failed by the education system, and would instead work to improve their reading skills. She proposes that all high school students be offered two years of debt-free higher education, either college or post-secondary training for skilled trades.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bridgemi.com/public-sector/what-michigan-schools-will-look-under-governor-whitmer-or-schuette|title=What Michigan schools will look like under Governor Whitmer or Schuette|date=October 25, 2018|accessdate=October 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Health care===\nWhitmer has said she would fight Republican efforts to take away protections for patients with preexisting conditions. In the State Senate, Whitmer successfully worked to expand Medicaid coverage in the state. She has spoken against single-payer healthcare as unrealistic. She has stated she would work to lower the cost of prescription drugs, and would get rid of Shuette's drug immunity law, which she believes protects drug companies from legal trouble if their drugs harm or kill people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2018/07/18/michigan-governor-race-gretchen-whitmer-blue-cross/|title=A Blue Cross CEO Encouraged a Michigan Woman to Get Into Politics. Now She's Running for Governor and Says Single Payer Is Unrealistic.|last=Jilani|first=Zaid|date=July 18, 2018|website=The Intercept-US|accessdate=October 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Taxation===\nIn March 2019 Whitmer proposed increasing the gasoline tax 45 cents per gallon to fund road repairs. If it is enacted Michigan will have the highest fuel tax in the [[United States]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/2019/03/04/whitmer-budget-road-funding-options/3055987002/|title=Gov. Gretchen Whitmer to propose 45-cent hike in fuel tax to fund Michigan roads|website=Detroit Free Press|accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWhitmer has two children with her first husband, Gary Shrewsbury. The couple divorced, and in 2011 she married dentist Marc Mallory, who has three children from his previous marriage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/local/michigan/2018/06/27/gretch-whitmer-profile-michigan-governor/698088002/|title=Whitmer rises to establishment choice in Democrats' gov race|work=Detroit News|accessdate=August 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gretchenwhitmer.com/bio/|title=Meet Gretchen \u2013 Gretchen Whitmer for Governor|work=Gretchen Whitmer for Governor|accessdate=August 10, 2018}}</ref> Whitmer and Mallory live in [[East Lansing, Michigan]], with her two daughters, Sherry and Sydney, and his three sons, Alex, Mason, and Winston.<ref name=\"monprofile\">{{cite news|url=http://www.oaklandlegalnews.com/washtenaw/1423164|title=Monday Profile: Gretchen Whitmer|date=April 11, 2016|work=Oakland Legal News|accessdate=December 25, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161226060218/http://www.oaklandlegalnews.com/washtenaw/1423164|archive-date=December 26, 2016|url-status=bot: unknown}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wlns.com/news/6-news-on-demand/skubick-whitmer-family-joins-in-run-for-governor/999903055|title=Skubick: Whitmer family joins in run for governor|last=VanderKolk|first=Kevin|date=January 4, 2017|work=WLNS|accessdate=August 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Gretchen Whitmer}}\n* [https://gretchenwhitmer.com/ Campaign website]\n* [http://www.votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=37868 Project Vote Smart \u2013 Senator Gretchen Whitmer (MI)] profile\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060526202257/http://www.michiganliberal.com/tag.do?tag=SD23 Michigan Liberal \u2013 SD23]\n* {{C-SPAN|Gretchen Whitmer}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-mi-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=Laura Baird}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Michigan House of Representatives]]<br>from the 70th district|years=2001\u20132003}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Judy Emmons]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael C. Murphy (Michigan politician)|Michael C. Murphy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Michigan House of Representatives]]<br>from the 69th district|years=2003\u20132006}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mark Meadows (Michigan politician)|Mark Meadows]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-mi-sen}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Virgil Bernero]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Michigan Senate]]<br>from the 23rd district|years=2006\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Curtis Hertel Jr.]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Prusi]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Minority Leader of the [[Michigan Senate]]|years=2011\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jim Ananich]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mark Schauer]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[Governor of Michigan]]|years=[[Michigan gubernatorial election, 2018|2018]]}}\n{{s-inc|rows=2|recent}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stacey Abrams]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Response to the State of the Union address]]|years=[[2020 State of the Union Address|2020]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rick Snyder]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Governor of Michigan]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before={{Incumbent VPOTUS}}|as=[[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]]}}\n{{s-ttl|rows=2|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Within Michigan}}\n{{s-aft|after=Mayor of city<br>in which event is held}}\n|-\n{{s-aft|after=Otherwise {{Incumbent U.S. House Speaker}}<br>{{nowrap|''as [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives]]''}}}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Asa Hutchinson]]|as=[[List of Governors of Arkansas|Governor of Arkansas]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Outside Michigan}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ron DeSantis]]|as=[[List of Governors of Florida|Governor of Florida]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of Michigan}}\n{{Current U.S. governors}}\n{{Michigan statewide political officials}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whitmer, Gretchen}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Michigan House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Michigan Democrats]]\n[[Category:Michigan state senators]]\n[[Category:Michigan State University College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Lansing, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Women state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Women state legislators in Michigan]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{short description|49th Governor of Michigan}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Gretchen Whitmer\n| order = 49th [[Governor of Michigan]]\n| lieutenant = [[Garlin Gilchrist]]\n| term_start = January 1, 2019\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Rick Snyder]]\n| successor = \n| image = Gov. Gretchen Whitmer (cropped).jpg\n| office1 = [[Ingham County, Michigan|Ingham County]] [[Prosecutor]]\n| term_start1 = July 21, 2016\n| term_end1 = December 31, 2016\n| predecessor1 = [[Stuart Dunnings III]]\n| successor1 = Carol Siemon\n| office2 = [[Minority leader|Minority Leader]] of the [[Michigan Senate]]\n| deputy2 = [[Steve Bieda]]\n| term_start2 = January 1, 2011\n| term_end2 = January 1, 2015\n| predecessor2 = [[Mike Prusi]]\n| successor2 = [[Jim Ananich]]\n| state_senate3 = Michigan\n| district3 = 23rd\n| term_start3 = March 21, 2006\n| term_end3 = January 1, 2015\n| predecessor3 = [[Virgil Bernero]]\n| successor3 = [[Curtis Hertel Jr.]]\n| office4 = Member of the <br>[[Michigan House of Representatives]]\n| term_start4 = January 1, 2001\n| term_end4 = March 21, 2006\n| predecessor4 = [[Laura Baird]]\n| successor4 = [[Mark Meadows (Michigan politician)|Mark Meadows]]\n| constituency4 = 70th district (2001\u20132003)<br>69th district (2003\u20132006)\n| birth_name = Gretchen Esther Whitmer\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1971|8|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Lansing, Michigan|Lansing]], [[Michigan]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse = Gary Shrewsbury (div.)<br>{{marriage|Marc Mallory|2011}}\n| children = 2\n| residence = [[Michigan Governor's Mansion|Governor's Mansion]]\n| education = [[Michigan State University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| website = {{url|michigan.gov/gov|Government website}}\n| signature = Whitmersig.jpg\n}}\n'''Gretchen Esther Whitmer''' (born August 23, 1971) is an American politician serving as the [[List of Governors of Michigan|49th]] [[governor of Michigan]]. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], she served in the [[Michigan House of Representatives]] from 2001 to 2006 and in the [[Michigan Senate]] from 2006 to 2015. \n\nBorn and raised in [[Michigan]] as the daughter of two lawyers, Whitmer graduated from [[Forest Hills Central High School]] near [[Grand Rapids, Michigan|Grand Rapids]], [[Michigan State University]], and the [[Michigan State University College of Law]]. She ran unsuccessfully for the state house in the 1990s before being elected in 2000. In 2006 she became a state senator, a position she kept until [[term limit|term limits]] forced her to step down in 2015. She was the Senate's first female Democratic leader from 2011 to 2015. In 2013, Whitmer gained national attention for a floor speech during a debate on [[abortion]] in which she shared her experience of being [[Sexual Assault|sexually assaulted]]. For six months in 2016, she was the [[prosecutor|county prosecutor]] for [[Ingham County, Michigan|Ingham County]].\n\nWhitmer was elected governor in [[2018 Michigan gubernatorial election|the 2018 gubernatorial election]], defeating Republican [[Attorney General of Michigan|Attorney General]] [[Bill Schuette]]. As governor, Whitmer has focused on healthcare and infrastructure. In February 2020, she was selected to give [[Response to the State of the Union address|the Democratic response]] to [[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump|Donald Trump's]] [[2020 State of the Union Address]]. She is the national co-chairwoman of the [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nGretchen Whitmer was born in 1971 in [[Lansing, Michigan]], as the eldest of three children to Sharon H. \"Sherry\" Reisig and Richard Whitmer, who were both lawyers.<ref name=\"LegalNews\">{{cite web|title=Monday Profile: Gretchen Whitmer|url=http://www.oaklandlegalnews.com/washtenaw/1423164|website=LegalNews.com|accessdate=March 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/name/sharon-whitmer-obituary?pid=182956096|title=SHARON WHITMER Obituary - Detroit, Michigan &#124; Legacy.com}}</ref> Her father served as head of the state's Department of Commerce under Governor [[William Milliken]] and was the president and [[CEO]] of [[Blue Cross Blue Shield of Michigan]] between 1988 and 2006.<ref name=\"CRAIN18\">{{cite news |title=Blue Cross takes punches in governor's race |url=http://www.crainsdetroit.com/article/20180708/news/665536/blue-cross-takes-punches-in-governors-race |accessdate=July 11, 2018 |work=[[Crain's Detroit Business]] |date=July 8, 2018}}</ref> Whitmer's mother worked as an assistant attorney general under [[Michigan Attorney General]] [[Frank J. Kelley|Frank Kelley]].<ref name=\"csgmidwest\">{{cite web|title=Stateline Profile Gretchen Whitmer|url=http://www.csgmidwest.org/publications/documents/p8Whitmer.pdf|website=csgmidwest.org/|accessdate=March 2, 2017}}</ref> Her parents divorced when she was 10 years old; she and her siblings moved with their mother to [[Grand Rapids, Michigan|Grand Rapids]]. Her father traveled from his home in Detroit to visit the family at least once a week.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/2018/05/24/gretchen-whitmer-governor-michigan/629845002/|title=Gretchen Whitmer's perplexing problem in race for Michigan governor|work=Detroit Free Press|accessdate=August 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhitmer graduated from [[Forest Hills Central High School]], just outside Grand Rapids.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mathews|first1=Reena|title=FHC alumna Senator Gretchen Whitmer is running for Governor|url=http://thecentraltrend.com/13375/showcase/senator-gretchen-whitmer-fhc-alumna-running-for-governor/|accessdate=March 2, 2017|work=The Central Trend|date=January 17, 2017}}</ref> She earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in communications from [[Michigan State University]] in 1993 and a [[Juris Doctor]] from [[Michigan State University College of Law|Detroit College of Law at Michigan State University]] in 1998.\n\n==State Legislature==\n===House of Representatives===\nWhitmer originally ran for the [[Michigan House of Representatives]] in the 1990s but was unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jilani |first1=Zaid |title=A Blue Cross CEO Encouraged a Michigan Woman to Get Into Politics. Now She\u2019s Running for Governor and Says Single Payer Is Unrealistic. |url=https://theintercept.com/2018/07/18/michigan-governor-race-gretchen-whitmer-blue-cross/ |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |publisher=The Intercept |date=18 July 2018}}</ref> In 2000, she tried again and was elected to represent the 23rd legislative district. She was reelected in 2002 and 2004.<ref name=MichManual>{{cite book | author = Michigan Legislative Service Bureau | title = Michigan Manual 2005\u20132006 | publisher = Legislative Council, State of Michigan | year = 2006 | location = Lansing | url = https://archive.org/details/michiganmanual00mich/page/129 | isbn = 1-878210-06-8 | accessdate = June 29, 2007 | page = [https://archive.org/details/michiganmanual00mich/page/129 129] | url-access = registration }}</ref>\n\n===State Senate===\nIn March 2006, Whitmer left the state house and became a [[Michigan State Senate|State Senator]]. She was elected and reelected in 2006 and 2010. In 2011, Whitmer's Democratic colleagues unanimously chose her to be the Senate Democratic Leader, making her the first woman to lead a party caucus in the Senate. She continued in that role for the remainder of her time there.<ref name=\"csgmidwest\" /> Due to [[term limit|term limits]], Whitmer was unable to run for reelection in 2014 and left office in 2015.<ref name=SenateDem>{{cite web|author=Michigan Senate Democrats |title=Michigan Senate Democrats: About Gretchen Whitmer |year=2007 |url=http://www.senate.mi.gov/whitmer/about.htm |accessdate=June 29, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070205183624/http://www.senate.mi.gov/whitmer/about.htm |archivedate=February 5, 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> In 2013, she received national recognition when she discussed her experience of being [[Sexual Assault|sexually assaulted]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Mitch |title=Who Is Gov. Gretchen Whitmer of Michigan, the Democrats\u2019 Answer to Trump? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/04/us/politics/gretchen-whitmer-state-of-the-union.html |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |publisher=The New York Times |date=4 February 2020}}</ref> She told the story during a debate about [[abortion]] rights, particularly for victims of [[rape]], arguing victims should be allowed to terminate pregnancies which resulted from rape.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Abbey-Lambertz |first1=Kate |title=Lawmaker Bravely Reveals She Was Victim Of Rape In Emotional 'Abortion Insurance' Debate |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/gretchen-whitmer-rape_n_4432203 |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |publisher=The Huffington Post |date=December 12, 2013 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Ingham County Prosecutor==\nOn May 11, 2016, it was announced that the judges of Michigan's 30th Judicial Circuit Court had unanimously selected Whitmer to serve the remaining six months of the term of outgoing Ingham County Prosecutor Stuart Dunnings III<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lansingstatejournal.com/story/news/local/capitol/2016/05/11/whitmer-chosen-interim-ingham-county-prosecutor/84248374/ |title=Whitmer chosen for interim Ingham County prosecutor |work=Lansing State Journal |author=Justin A. Hicks |date=May 11, 2016}}</ref> after he was arrested on March 14, 2016, and charged with 11 counts of involvement with a prostitute and four counts of willful neglect of duty.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/index.ssf/2016/03/ingham_county_prosecutor_alleg.html |title=Ingham County Prosecutor allegedly engaged prostitutes 'hundreds of times' |work=MLive Media Group |author=Emily Lawler |date=March 14, 2016 |accessdate=May 11, 2016}}</ref> In a letter dated March 29, 2016, Dunnings announced he would resign effective July 2.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/jackson/index.ssf/2016/03/stuart_dunnings_informs_ingham.html |title=Stuart Dunnings informs Ingham County he is resigning as prosecutor |work=Jackson Citizen Patriot |author=Benjamin Raven |date=March 29, 2016 |accessdate=May 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn June 21, 2016, Whitmer was administered the oath of office as prosecutor by Ingham County Circuit Court Chief Judge Janelle Lawless. She said her top priorities during her six months of service would be to determine if any other officials in the prosecutor's office knew about Dunnings's alleged crimes and to change how the office handled domestic violence and sexual assault cases.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lansingstatejournal.com/story/news/local/2016/06/21/whitmer-looking-forward-starting-prosecutor/86139690/ |title=Whitmer 'looking forward' to starting as prosecutor |authors=Matt Mencarini and Justin A. Hinkley |work=Lansing State Journal |date=June 22, 2016 |accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 22, 2016, Whitmer issued an 11-page report on whether Dunnings's alleged criminal activity had affected cases handled by the office. The report concluded that employees \"were never asked to compromise a case or look the other way\" and that she had \"...full confidence that any problem that had existed in this office left with Mr. Dunnings.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lansingstatejournal.com/story/news/local/watchdog/2016/07/22/problems-left-mr-dunnings-whitmer-says/87431782/ |title=Cases unaffected by Dunnings' alleged crimes, Whitmer says |author=Justin A. Hinkley |work=Lansing State Journal |date=July 22, 2016 |accessdate=August 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://pa.ingham.org/Portals/PA/Documents/Report%20on%20the%20Status%20of%20the%20Ingham%20County%20Prosecutor's%20Office.pdf |title=Report on the Status of the Ingham County Prosecutor's Office |publisher=Ingham County Prosecutor's Office |first=Gretchen |last=Whitmer |date=July 22, 2016 |accessdate=August 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160803145021/http://pa.ingham.org/Portals/PA/Documents/Report%20on%20the%20Status%20of%20the%20Ingham%20County%20Prosecutor's%20Office.pdf |archive-date=August 3, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Whitmer's term expired on December 31, 2016.\n\n==Governorship==\n[[File:Michigan National Guard members participate in inauguration, Adjutant General swearing-in 190101-F-VX133-049.jpg|thumb|Whitmer speaking at a National Guard ceremony in January 2019]]\n\n===2018 election===\nOn January 3, 2017, Whitmer announced she would run in the [[Michigan gubernatorial election, 2018|2018 Michigan gubernatorial race]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Whitmer|first1=Gretchen|title=I'm ready \u2014 are you?|url=https://medium.com/@gretchenwhitmer_12225/im-ready-are-you-c150e9f75e97|website=Medium|accessdate=June 3, 2017|date=January 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn August 7, 2018, Whitmer became the Democratic nominee for governor of Michigan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/07/us/politics/gretchen-whitmer-michigan-election-results.html|title=Whitmer and Schuette Win Michigan Governor's Nominations|website=nytimes.com|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref> She won all 83 counties in the state in the Democratic primary<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://miboecfr.nictusa.com/election/results/2018PRI_CENR.html/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=August 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180809220343/https://miboecfr.nictusa.com/election/results/2018PRI_CENR.html |archive-date=August 9, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>.  \n\nIn July 2018, Republican officials accused Whitmer of supporting the movement to [[Abolish ICE|abolish]] [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement|ICE]], a claim Whitmer disputed. She said that if elected she would focus on improving Michigan's \"fundamentals\", such as schools, roads, and water systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/74dead3614e346e495e064c3e42a6f13|title=AP Interview: Whitmer focuses on 'fundamentals' like roads|date=September 15, 2018|website=apnews.com|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhitmer's main opponent was Republican [[Bill Schuette]], the term-limited [[Michigan Attorney General|Attorney General of Michigan]]. The two candidates met for a debate on October 12, 2018, in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan|Grand Rapids]] at [[WOOD-TV]]. A second debate was held at [[WDIV-TV|WDIV]] studios in Detroit on October 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlive.com/news/index.ssf/2018/10/gretchen_whitmer_bill_schuette.html|title=Gretchen Whitmer, Bill Schuette butt heads at first gubernatorial debate|website=mlive.com|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhitmer defeated Schuette in the November 6 election by nearly a 10-point margin.<ref>{{cite web |title=Michigan Election Results |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/11/06/us/elections/results-michigan-elections.html |website=New York Times |publisher=The Associated Press |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nWhitmer describes herself as a progressive Democrat<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Smith|first=Mitch|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/04/us/politics/gretchen-whitmer-state-of-the-union.html|title=Democrats Turn to Gov. Gretchen Whitmer of Michigan for Trump State of the Union Response|date=2020-02-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> who can work with state legislators from different political perspectives.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAs both a gubernatorial candidate and as governor, one of Whitmer's key pledges was to \"fix the damn roads\", a reference to Michigan's struggling infrastructure. But her initial post-election plan to fund road repairs with a 45-cent-per-gallon gas tax increase was deeply unpopular, with one poll finding it opposed by 75% of Michigan voters, including majorities of both Democrats and independents.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Livengood |first1=Chad |title=Poll: 75% oppose Whitmer's 45-cent gas tax hike plan |url=https://www.crainsdetroit.com/voices-chad-livengood/poll-75-oppose-whitmers-45-cent-gas-tax-hike-plan |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |work=Crain's Detroit Business |publisher=Crain Communications |date=April 18, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Even Democratic legislators in Michigan's Republican-controlled legislature largely declined to support the plan, which would have nearly tripled Michigan's gas tax and potentially made it the highest in the nation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Beggin |first1=Riley|title=Michigan House Dem leader says Whitmer\u2019s 45-cent gas tax is probably dead |url=https://www.bridgemi.com/michigan-government/michigan-house-dem-leader-says-whitmers-45-cent-gas-tax-probably-dead |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |work=Bridge Michigan |publisher=Center for Michigan |date=August 29, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news |last1=Malewitz|first1=Jim |last2=Wilkinson |first2=Mike |title=Gretchen Whitmer\u2019s plan to fix Michigan roads: Nearly triple gas tax |url=https://www.bridgemi.com/michigan-government/gretchen-whitmers-plan-fix-michigan-roads-nearly-triple-gas-tax |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |work=Bridge Michigan |publisher=Center for Michigan |date=March 4, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nWhitmer's first budget earmarked several billions of dollars for investment in infrastructure.<ref name=\"Highlights\">{{cite news|last1=CNN|first1=Devan Cole|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/04/politics/who-is-gretchen-whitmer-state-of-the-union-response/index.html|title=Michigan governor's response to Trump's State of the Union to highlight state Democrats want to win in 2020|date=February 4, 2020|accessdate=February 4, 2020|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Law |first1=Tara |title=Gretchen Whitmer Is Giving the Democrats' State of the Union Response. Here's What to Know |url=https://time.com/5777872/gretchen-whitmer-democratic-response-state-of-the-union/ |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |work=Time |publisher=TIME |date=February 4, 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Neavling |first1=Steve |title=Whitmer breaks pledge to 'fix the damn roads' under new budget |url=https://www.metrotimes.com/news-hits/archives/2019/09/09/whitmer-breaks-pledge-to-fix-the-damn-roads-under-new-budget |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |publisher=Detroit Metro Times |date=September 9, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> In 2019, she struggled with the Republican-controlled legislature to pass a budget and made several concessions.<ref name=\"Highlights\" />\n\nThe gubernatorial election and national conversation during Whitmer's time in office focused largely on healthcare. During the election, she was the only Democratic candidate not to support a [[single-payer healthcare]] system.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jilani |first1=Zaid |title=A Blue Cross CEO Encouraged a Michigan Woman to Get Into Politics. Now She\u2019s Running for Governor and Says Single Payer Is Unrealistic. |url=https://theintercept.com/2018/07/18/michigan-governor-race-gretchen-whitmer-blue-cross/ |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |publisher=The Intercept |date=July 18, 2018}}</ref> As governor, she has focused on women's healthcare and [[Medicaid]] expansion.<ref name=\"Highlights\"></ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Whitmer was selected to deliver the Democratic response to [[Donald Trump]]'s [[2020 State of the Union Address]]. Michigan is considered a [[swing state]] in the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 presidential election]], and it was speculated that Democrats hoped selecting Whitmer would bolster their chance of winning the state.<ref name=\"Highlights\"></ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lawler |first1=Emily |last2=Barrett |first2=Michael |title=5 things to know about Michigan Gov. Gretchen Whitmer as she takes the national stage |url=https://www.mlive.com/news/2020/02/5-things-to-know-about-michigan-gov-gretchen-whitmer-as-she-takes-the-national-stage.html |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |publisher=Michigan Live |date=4 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Mitch |title=Democrats Turn to Gov. Gretchen Whitmer of Michigan for Trump State of the Union Response |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/04/us/politics/gretchen-whitmer-state-of-the-union.html |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |publisher=The New York Times |date=February 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin |title=Michigan House of Representatives District 70 Democratic Primary, 2000<ref>{{cite web | url=http://miboecfr.nictusa.com/election/results/00pri/ | title=2000 Michigan Election Results | publisher=Michigan Department of State |date=September 28, 2016 |accessdate=September 26, 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate w